<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadian Housing Sector Rallying </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Canada's hard-pressed housing
sector has started rallying because of low prices and mortgage
rates.
</P>
<P>
The value of residential building permits has increased for two
straight quarters following six consecutive quarterly declines,
Statistics Canada reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Between April and June this year, municipalities issued
building permits for new housing worth 2.78 billion U.S. dollars,
up 0.5 percent over the first three months of the year.
</P>
<P>
This was the highest quarterly level since late 1994, the
federal agency said.
</P>
<P>
The increase, which followed a jump of almost 20 percent in the
first quarter of this year, was due mainly to a rise in the value
of permits for multi-family dwellings.
</P>
<P>
As building permits take up to six months to result in a start,
the latest increase in the value of permits could result in more
new home construction, and possibly more jobs, by the end of this
year, the agency said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
