<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Croats, Muslims Reach Agreement On Mostar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Bosnian Croats and Muslims
signed a deal on Tuesday on the political structure of Mostar,
averting a major crisis in the seven-month peace process of this
Balkan country.
</P>
<P>
"We have reached agreement, which was signed by both parties,"
said Dragan Gasic, a spokesman for European Union, which has
administered the ethnically-torn Mostar in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
There are no immediate details about the agreement, which came
after rounds of drawn-out negotiations involving Muslim and Croats
officials as well as EU representatives.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the EU threatened that it would pull out of Mostar,
if no agreement was reached by midnight Saturday, but postponed
the deadline after negotiators failed to meet it.
</P>
<P>
The Mostar crisis erupted when Croats boycotted the
newly-elected city council, on the ground that there were
"irregularities" in the June 30 local elections in which Croats
lost to their Muslim opponents.
</P>
<P>
The EU countries, as well as the United States, have exerted
strong pressure on Bosnian Croats and Croatia to end the boycott,
for fear that the move, if not stopped, would set bad precedent
for the September nation-wide elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
