<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France to Begin Consultations with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- France will begin consultations
with its European Union (EU) partners on measures of reprisals
against the U.S. d'Amato law signed Monday by U.S. President Bill
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
The law reinforces embargo against Iran and Libya by banning
heavy investments by foreign companies in energy section of the
two countries, causing widespread alarm in Europe whose oil
consumption largely depends on imports from them.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Ministry vice-spokesman Yves Doutrizux said that
consultations with EU partners will begin to prepare for measures
of reprisals for possible losses caused by d'Amato law, named
after Republican Senator Alfonso d'Amato of New York, who is the
main author of the law.
</P>
<P>
He said that d'Amato law is "in the same line of"
Helms-Burton law, which reinforces embargo against Cuba by banning
trade between foreign companies and the Caribbean nation.
</P>
<P>
"Now, the ball is in the camp of American administration. It
has the legislation which will allow it to act concretely and to
punish non-American enterprises, but will it do it? We hope that
reason will prevail," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He said that the European Council had asked the European
Commission to prepare for some measures of reprisals against
Helms-Burton law, and these measures "are on the desk."
</P>
<P>
Among the measures is the making a legislation allowing
European enterprises to obtain compensations for losses caused by
U.S. court rulings, and of establishing a black list of U.S.
enterprises which try to take advantage of the Helms-Burton law
against Europeans.
</P>
<P>
"One should use imagination in making measures of reaction by
taking into account what d'Amato law is, which is not all the same
(as Helms -Burton law)... in ways of application," Doutrizux
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Criticizes Israel for Delaying Hebron Redeployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) President Yasser Arafat today sharply criticized Israel for
delaying its army redeployment in the West Bank town of Hebron,
and lifting a freeze on Jewish settlement activity.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the Palestinian Council (PC) in the West Bank town
Ramallah, Arafat called for a plan to stop Israel expanding the
Jewish settlements.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, the Israeli government authorized simpler
procedure for granting permission for Jewish constructions in the
West Bank and the Gaza Strip, lifting a four-year long settlement
building freeze imposed by the previous government.
</P>
<P>
Israeli media pointed out that the message appeared to be that
the freeze of settlement activity is over, although no
operational decision was immediately made.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, PC Speaker Ahmed Qreia (Abu Alla) said today that
the Palestinians would not open new negotiations on the Hebron
redeployment, saying the Israeli troops should pullout from the
city, in accordance with the Oslo accords.
</P>
<P>
His remarks came after Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu said Monday, during his trip to Jordan, that Israel
would be ready to negotiate the Hebron issue in a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak
Mordehai said Monday that, to his best knowledge, no date had been
set for the redeployment of the Israeli army in Hebron.
</P>
<P>
According to the Oslo 2 accord, the Israeli army was supposed
to pullback from about 85 percent of Hebron by March 28, however,
following a series of suicide bombing attacks, former Prime
Minister Shimon Peres delayed the redeployment.
</P>
<P>
In May, the former Israeli government announced that the
army's withdrawal from Hebron would be carried out after the May
29 general elections, due to security reasons.
</P>
<P>
However, Peres, defeated by Likud chairman Netanyahu, said
after the elections that he would leave the decision of the
redeployment to the new prime minister and his government.
</P>
<P>
Hebron, some 30 kilometers southwest of Jerusalem, is a
place of pilgrimage for Christians, Jews and Muslims alike,
and tradition has it that patriarchs Abraham, Isaac, Jacob and
their wives are all buried in the Machpelah Cave (Haram
al-Khalil).
</P>
<P>
There are some 400 Jewish settlers now living in the
center of Hebron, who moved back to the city's old Jewish
neighborhood after the 1967 war, during which Israel took over
the town from the Jordanian authority.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, surrounding the Jewish community, there are more
than 200,000 Palestinian residents living in most other parts
of the city.
</P>
<P>
During his election campaign, Netanyahu had said that he would
like Hebron to be part of the final status arrangements with the
Palestinians, but, at the same time, he also said he would stand
by the international agreements.
</P>
<P>
So far, Netanyahu repeatedly said he has been studying the
issue of the redeployment in Hebron, but giving no date when
he would make the final decision.
</P>
<P>
Early last month, American sources revealed that the Israeli
premier, during his first official visit to the U.S. since he took
office in June, told President Bill Clinton at their private
meeting that he would seek a way to implement the redeployment in
Hebron. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
