<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Somali Teachers Protest for End of Food Ration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Over 120 teachers took to the
streets in South Mogadishu today, protesting against the
termination of their food rations by the World Food Program
(WFP).
</P>
<P>
A document signed by G. Van Dijk, WFP's representative in
Uganda, said the organization's "Food for Work" program would be
ended from July 31, 1996. More than 2,288 Mogadishu teachers are
benefiting from the program.
</P>
<P>
WFP used to provide teachers with food valued at 50 U.S.
Dollars per month, but the ration was dropped dramatically by 6
U.S. Dollars per month before it was totally stopped last
October, according to the teachers.
</P>
<P>
"We don't understand the sharp decrease while the food prices
were increasing in the markets," said a teacher.
</P>
<P>
The humanitarian situation in Somalia in general and in South
Mogadishu in particular is worsening.
</P>
<P>
"We can only pass the stock that comes to us from Nairobi to
the concerned parties. We have nothing to explain," said Iddiris
Mohamed Osman, a spokesman of the organization. WFP's Mogadishu
office is currently run by local Somalis.
</P>
<P>
After the withdrawal of the Untied Nations peacekeeping forces
from Somalia, there were few aid agencies that worked in
Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
And the very few agencies that operated in South Mogadishu
have evacuated their international staff after the factional
fighting escalated in April this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
