<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Athletes Flies Home to Warm Welcome </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Russia welcomed its athletes home
as heroes on Tuesday after attending the Atlanta Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
President Boris Yeltsin, in an official statement quoted by
Interfax news agency, said the team, which won 26 gold medals to
the United States' 44, had "upheld the nation's glorious
sporting traditions."
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin was not among officials who welcomed team members in a
low-key ceremony at Moscow's Sheremetyevo Airport.
</P>
<P>
Russia's performance in team events in Atlanta was
disappointing compared to individual successes.
</P>
<P>
"Steps need to be taken quickly at a state level if we don't
want Russia to become a backwater of world sport," Vitaly
Smirnov, the president of the Russian Olympic Committee, said
earlier.
</P>
<P>
Moskovsky Komsomolets criticised the heavy commercialism of
the Atlanta Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
Leading sports daily Sport Express gave the fortnight in
Atlanta 10 out of 10 for the quality of competition. But it too
slammed the organisers for, among other things, the athletes'
village and the transport system, which got just one out of 10.
</P>
</TEXT>
