<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Geologists Told That They Should Pay More Attention to Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 6 (Xinhua) -- A prominent European geologist
says that it is high time for geologists, who always work in
remote areas, to pay more attention to cities.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Peter J. Cook, president of the Association of the
Geological Survey of the European Union, said in an interview with
Xinhua here today that our living space has been threated by
increasing population, pollution, and the over-exploitation of
underground water.
</P>
<P>
"There is a lot to do in the cities," he pointed out, and "we
should work less in traditional areas and more in cities."
</P>
<P>
Cook worked in Australia, the US, Antarctica, and France before
he was appointed director of the British Geological Survey.
</P>
<P>
He was selected as one of four geologists to give a keynote
address at the 30th International Geological Congress, which
opened here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"Sustainability embodies the concept that we must not use
resources or degrade the environment in a manner that will impact
adversely on future generations," he says.
</P>
<P>
He noted that even the most basic human requirement of air,
water and space to live in are under great pressure in many areas,
and that the sustainability of our life system depends on an
extraordinary complex interplay of factors involving the
availability and use of water, air, soils, land, energy and
minerals.
</P>
<P>
"Geoscience is a key to this understanding," he points out, and
better documentating, monitoring, modeling, and understanding of
the system is essential to geologists.
</P>
<P>
A research group from BGS has succeeded in pumping water down
to the ground and store natural gas in rocks, he says, but science
alone does not offer a solution. "It is essential to strengthen
communications between the sciences, and also between managers,
policy-makers and others concerned with the consequences of change
and the unsustainable exploitation of resources and the
environment."
</P>
<P>
Change is part of the natural system, but clearly the type,
magnitude and rate of change now affecting many areas is not
"natural", he said in his speech.
</P>
<P>
"We must carefully document those changes and develop a better
understanding of the processes involved, for it is inevitable that
the anthropogenic impact will increase, " he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No "Middle Way" for Dalai Lama: Scholars (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Two Chinese scholars said today
that the only way out for the Dalai Lama is to give up the pursuit
of "Independence of Tibet" completely - there is no "middle way".
</P>
<P>
Dainzhub Angbun, vice-president of the Central University for
Nationalities, and Yang Gongsu, a renowned Tibetologist and Han
scholar, made the remark in an interview with Xinhua. They have
done research on some recent speeches of the Dalai Lama in
Britain's Parliament and in other places.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the British Parliament on July 16, the Dalai Lama
said that he has adopted a "middle-way" approach and was willing
"to enter into negotiations (with the central government) on the
basis of an agenda that does not include the independence."
</P>
<P>
The two scholars pointed out that by saying so Dalai has
deceived the international community. At heart, he dreams of
"independence", said Angbun, an Tibetan, adding that the Dalai's
real intention is to internationalize the Tibet question.
</P>
<P>
In the same speech the Dalai Lama said that "historically and
according to international law Tibet is an independent country
under Chinese occupation."
</P>
<P>
Commenting on this remark, the two scholars expressed doubt
about whether there is any need for the Dalai Lama to negotiate
with the central government if he ignores history to such a degree.
</P>
<P>
Angbun said that, in the 13th century, China's Yuan Dynasty
(1271-1368) began registering households, collecting taxes, and
imposing corvee duties in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
"This means China's central government exercised its
sovereignty, in a modern sense, over Tibet," the university head
noted.
</P>
<P>
Yang remarked that "judging from international law, there is no
evidence that justifies the saying that Tibet has ever been an
independent state."
</P>
<P>
Although Britain and other colonial powers consistently plotted
the "independence of Tibet" at the start of the century, all
efforts came to naught, Yang pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Since ancient times, it has never occurred to people to build
an "independent state" in Tibet, said the two scholars, adding
that, in accordance with available materials, the slogan of
"independence of Tibet" was initially raised by the British
imperialists for the purpose of invading Tibet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No "Middle Way" for Dalai Lama: Scholars (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The two scholars said that some "evidence justifying the
independence of Tibet" propagated by the Dalai clique and certain
western scholars is not supportable.
</P>
<P>
One piece of "evidence" cited by western scholars is the "Lhasa
Convention", which the British army compelled three Tibetan major
temples to sign in 1904. It was not effective because the high
commissioner stationed in Tibet by the Qing government refused to
sign it.
</P>
<P>
Although the Qing government conceded the "Lhasa Convention" as
an affiliated contract while signing the Beijing Treaty, China's
sovereignty over Tibet was safeguarded because the Beijing Treaty
stipulated that "Britain should never occupy Tibet and interfere
in any political event in Tibet."
</P>
<P>
Another piece of "evidence" is the Simla Convention of 1914,
masterminded by Britain, where McMahon, the British
representative, tried to bully Tibet's representative into
recognizing the so-called McMahon Line, which ceded large areas of
land to Tibet.
</P>
<P>
As the Chinese representative attending the meeting did not
sign the agreement, and insisted on Tibet's being a part of China,
the British imperilists failed yet another time.
</P>
<P>
The Dalai Lama and some western scholars have also referred to
the announcement about driving the Sichuan Army out of Tibet, made
by the 13th Dalai Lama after the 1911 revolution led by Dr. Sun
Yat-sen which overthrew the Qing Dynasty, as a "declaration of
independence of Tibet."
</P>
<P>
However, the two scholars point out, that circular did not
mention the "independence" of Tibet, and it was the British who
intentionally rendered "snow land" as "country" in English.
</P>
<P>
The announcement reflected the conflicts among various domestic
separatist regimes at the time, but it had nothing to do with the
issue of "independence".
</P>
<P>
The so-called "independence of Tibet", the university
vice-president said, is virtually part of the invasion of Tibet by
imperialist powers.
</P>
<P>
The fact that the Dalai clique is asking for support from
certain anti-China powers, which in the past attempted to colonize
Tibet, is a betrayal of the interests of the Chinese nation,
including those of the Tibetan people, Dainzhub Angbun
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No "Middle Way" for Dalai Lama: Scholars (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As an expert on the history of relationships between Tibet's
local regime and the central government, Angbun said that in the
middle of the 14th century, power was granted to local heads of
Tibet by China's emperors.
</P>
<P>
During the Qing Dynasty, the titles of the Dalai and Panchen
Lamas, as well as the system of reincarnation of living Buddhas,
were created by the central government, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Dalai clique and some western scholars also said that Tibet
was once a tributary state of China, and as a result, China had no
sovereignty over it.
</P>
<P>
Angbun said that the features of a tributary state are as
follow: it is not part of the other country's territory; the
central government does not send ministers and does not interfere
in the replacement of rulers of the state; and periodic tribute to
the central government is part of it, but tax obligation is
not. Therefore, Tibet could not be classed as a tributary state.
</P>
<P>
The 86-year-old Yang, a professor at Beijing University, was
assistant to the representative of the central government
stationed in Tibet, after the peaceful liberation of Tibet in 1950.
</P>
<P>
After working in Tibet for 13 years, he became the Chinese
ambassador to Nepal and several other countries, and was in India
and western European countries, as a result of which, he is quite
familiar with the Dalai Lama and his government-in-exile.
</P>
<P>
Yang said that, while in Tibet, he had close contacts with the
Dalai Lama because of his work, and that there was "not much of a
barrier between them, such as was often found between higher and
lower officials."
</P>
<P>
At that time, Yang said, "the Dalai Lama was intelligent, wise,
eager to learn. He not only supported the central government, but
also loved the motherland."
</P>
<P>
After the Dalai Lama went abroad under duress, he began to seek
help from anti-China forces, Yang said, and "I felt a regret for
the fact that the Dalai Lama, under the influence of reactionary
forces inside his government-in-exile, ultimately became the tool
of anti-China forces and the head of the "independence of Tibet"
movement.
</P>
<P>
The current "independence" movement that surrounds the Dalai
Lama is primarily made up of former Tibetan aristocrats, who grew
up in a closed environment, and had little contact with the Han
people, Yang said.
</P>
<P>
They received a western education after their departure from
Tibet, Yang noted, and "as a result, they could not represent the
real interests of Tibetans as they are miles away from the real
lives and the thinking of the great masses of Tibet." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
