<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada to License Fertility Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian government is set to
regulate fertility industry by licensing researchers, doctors and
possibly drug companies that work with human fetal tissues,
embryos, eggs and sperm.
</P>
<P>
The licensing move is proposed as the next phase of a new
policy to deal with the business and science of human
reproduction.
</P>
<P>
Its goal is to give the federal government a clear picture of
what's happening in the infertility clinics and research
laboratories across Canada and a way to exert control over
practices that now go largely unregulated, today's Globe and Mail
newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
Right now, the Canadian government doesn't know how many
private or public clinics there are in the country offering in
vitro fertilization and donor insemination, or who is doing embryo
or fetal tissue research.
</P>
<P>
The licensing regime will be designed to cover a broad range of
medical procedures and research projects that aren't prohibited
under a bill tabled in June in the House of Commons.
</P>
<P>
The controversial New Reproduction and Genetic Technologies
Act, which is expected to be debated when the Commons return in
the fall, bans 13 practices, including the sale of human embryos,
eggs and sperm. The sanctions include fines of up to 365,000 U.S.
dollars and a maximum prison term of 10 years.
</P>
<P>
The licensing package will be tabled after the bill is passed,
and will become part of it, the newspaper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft to Speed up Graphics Displaying </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Computer software giant
Microsoft Corp. is mounting an ambitious bid to change the way
graphics are displayed on personal computer screens.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal reported today that the company is to
launch a two-year research project coded as Talisman, which is to
concentrate on a special microchip to make PCs more powerful in
displaying three-dimensional images at ultra-high speed.
</P>
<P>
Although Microsoft has never been directly involved in
designing chips before -- and will depend on other companies to
prove the concept works in silicon -- some experts believe
Talisman is a breakthrough that many hardware companies will
license and bring to market by the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates said a key goal of the company is
to make computers that can effectively interpret speech,
handwriting and video footage.
</P>
<P>
The paper said the next version of Microsoft's
word-processing software, for example, uses the research group's
techniques for interpreting human speech in an unusually
sophisticated grammar-checking device.  
</P>
</TEXT>
