<HEADLINE> Kuwait Backs German Initiative on Mines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait today voiced its
support for a German initiative on banning production and using of
anti-personnel mines and eliminating all planted mines scattered
around the globe.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti First Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister
Sheikh Sabah Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah declared that "Kuwait fully backs
the German initiative" and described it as "positive and effective
and can take part in eliminating the dangerous problem of mines,"
according to the official Kuwait News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The initiative was put forward by German Foreign Minister Klaus
Kinkel on July 18, who called for a diplomatic campaign to
restrict producing, exporting and planting anti-personnel mines.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sabah stressed on the necessity of an international support
for the German initiative.
</P>
<P>
According to international statistics, mines kill and deform
over 20,000 people in some 65 countries annually, including
Kuwait. At present, a total of 60 countries have joined the
U.N. May 3 Protocol over banning the production and exporting of
mines.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sabah attacked Iraqi troops which left "hundred of thousands
of different types of mines" when they withdrew from Kuwait on
February 26, 1991.
</P>
<P>
He said the Kuwaiti people were still suffering from the
human, psychological and environmental impact of the mines which
were planted by the Iraqi forces during the occupation.
</P>
<P>
"The Kuwaiti government, neighboring and friendly countries
have been working to eliminate them," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
