<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak Sends Message to Lebanese President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese President Elias Hrawi
received here today a verbal message from Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak which dealt with the results of his recent visit to
the U.S. and the stalled Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Ahamed Maher, Egyptian charge d'affaires to Lebanon, said that
he was entrusted by Mubarak to convey the urgent oral message.
</P>
<P>
He said that Mubarak and U.S. President Bill Clinton, when they
met in Washington on July 30, discussed the so-called "Lebanon
First" proposal put forward by the new Israeli government.
</P>
<P>
"Mubarak-Clinton meeting dealt with this issue, but as you know
that it was only a circulating idea, not an official one," the
Egyptian diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
"Of course all the problems related to the peace arrangements
in the region were discussed by President Mubarak in Washington,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Under Israel's "Lebanon First" proposal, the Jewish state will
pull its troops out of a 850-square-kilometer buffer zone in
southern Lebanon in exchange for Syria's help in disarming the
pro-Iranian Hezbollah guerillas and a mechanism safeguarding the
security on the Lebanese-Israeli border.
</P>
<P>
At the end of their talks in Washington, both Clinton and
Mubarak refrained from making mention of the proposal, but they
pledged to do their utmost to revive the Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the Lebanese President visited Damascus and held a
lengthy talks with Syrian President Hafez Assad. They reportedly
discussed the "Lebanon First" proposal.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman of the Syrian president said afterwards that
the two leaders "discussed the peace process and the negative
impacts of the Israeli policy on the progress of the talks."
</P>
<P>
"They stressed the importance of the continuation of full
coordination and the unity of their moves to achieve a just
and comprehensive peace based on the land-for-peace principle,"
the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
This morning, Hrawi had a meeting in the Beirut Presidential
Palace with House Speaker Nabih Berri and Prime Minister Rafik
Hariri and informed them of his talks with al-Assad in the Syrian
capital.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, the Lebanese house speaker left Beirut
immediately for Damascus to meet the Syrian president.
</P>
<P>
Hariri is also expected to visit the Syrian capital Wednesday
to meet Vice President Abdel Halim Khaddam, according to
well-informed Lebanese sources.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese leaders have announced their refusal of Israel's
unilateral withdrawal proposal and condemned it as an attempt
to separate Lebanon from Syria in their peace talks with the
Jewish state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
