<HEADLINE> Baby Fish Better Protected in Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Baby fish in Cambodia have
been better protected thanks to the effective measures taken by
the government to stop catching of the fish, local press reported
here today.
</P>
<P>
The illegal fishing has been reduced by 70 percent this year
compared to the previous year, said May Sam Oeun, undersecretary
of state for the Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The capturing of baby fish is prohibited between May and
October in the Tonle Sap, Tonle Bassac and Mekong rivers,
according to a law for fishing. Illegal trafficking of baby fish
is draining away one of Cambodia's principal natural resources.
</P>
<P>
Mr. Oeun said that most of the young fish captured are fattened
up for a year and then used in paste and soups. He alleged that
some members of the military had made catching baby fish "a
business," so his department needed adequate funds to protect his
inspectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
