<HEADLINE> Hiroshima Marks 51st Anniversary of A-bomb Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Some 50,000 people in the Japanese
city of Hiroshima gathered today at the city's Peace Memorial Park
to commemorate the victims of the atomic bomb attack 51 years ago
and pray for peace with a series of ceremonies, Kyodo News said.
</P>
<P>
After a memorial service to the dead held near the epicenter of
the blast, Takashi Hiraoka, mayor of Hiroshima, delivered the
annual peace declaration and renewed local residents' calling for
global abolition of nuclear arms.
</P>
<P>
Hiraoka emphasized that Hiroshima should be made a creative,
prospective and peaceful city.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of pupils read their peace declaration,
promising to live on bravely for the world peace.
</P>
<P>
Besides Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto and other Japanese
attendants, some 450 foreign guests including people from such
Asian countries as South Korea and China also participated in the
gattering, Kyodo News said.
</P>
<P>
On the same day in 1945, the U.S. B-29 bomber Enola Gay dropped
an atomic bomb on Hiroshima to speed an end to War War II. Death
toll in the attack amounted to 140,000 by the end of 1945.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the memorial ceremony has been held annually.
</P>
</TEXT>
