<HEADLINE> Britain Faces More Clashes with EU Partners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The British government is heading
for a collision with its European Union (EU) partners over various
issues on European integration at the Intergovernmental
Conference, according to the European Policy Forum.
</P>
<P>
The European Policy Forum, a British cross-party think-tank,
said in a research report that the British government is in a
minority of one on 35 issues and opposed 98 out of 148 proposals,
which are put forward for the Intergovernmental Conference.
</P>
<P>
In talks with the Irish presidency of the EU, details have
emerged to indicate that British disagreement with its EU partners
extends far beyond the main row over adopting the single European
currency in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The issues on which Britain is isolated include the extension
of qualified majority voting, the social chapter, the powers the
European parliament and the reform of the European Court of
Justice.
</P>
<P>
Britain's rejection of 98 EU proposals is in sharp contrast
with 29 by Germany, 39 by France and 42 by Sweden, which is the
highest number of rejections by a Scandinavian member state.
</P>
<P>
The Forum pointed out that it "seems unlikely" that all these
differences can be quickly resolved within the present structures
of the EU.
</P>
<P>
Graham Mather, president of the Forum and a Conservative MEP,
is reported as saying on Tuesday, "This shows it is not just the
single currency that Britain is opposing, underlining the need for
a referendum, but also suggests that Britain may have to negotiate
a flexible agreement on a whole range of issues." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
