<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eurotunnel Traffic Hits Record in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Eurotunnel, the Anglo-French
operator of the Channel tunnel, announced Monday that the numbers
of passengers and vehicles through the tunnel rose sharply in July
and its cross-Channel market share was further increased.
</P>
<P>
The company, still locked in tough negotiations with banks over
rescheduling its 8.4 billion pounds (13 billion US dollars) of
loans, said that a record 240,000 tourist vehicles used its Le
Shuttle rail service last month, an increase of 110 percent on the
same month last year and 31 percent up on this June.
</P>
<P>
Eurotunnel said that last weekend alone saw 31,000 cars and
coaches passing through the tunnel, the equivalent to about
100,000 passengers and more than a fifth of the traffic through
the tunnel in the whole of last August.
</P>
<P>
Le Shuttle freight services handled some 54,000 journeys by
trucks and lorries, an increase of 45 percent on the previous
July. Tons of freight increased by 35 percent from 158,000 to
214,000.
</P>
<P>
The number of passengers using high-speed Eurostar trains went
over the mark of 500,000 for the first time in July, a 72 percent
increase on the total for last July. Just over 2.7 million
passengers have traveled on Eurostar trains so far this year.
</P>
<P>
The company also claimed an increased cross-Channel market
share for July, with its service taking 44 percent of the car
market and 45 percent of the truck market up from the 40 percent
at the start of the year.
</P>
<P>
The encouraging figures for Eurotunnel follow an increasingly
intense commercial battle with the ferry operators and the
short-haul airlines. The group reduced its main return fare by 50
percent in May.
</P>
<P>
The introduction of special offers, including deals on
duty-free goods for travelers using Le Shuttle services, had also
helped boost trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Underscores Merits of Breast-feeding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization
(WHO) on Tuesday called on the world community to support
breast-feeding as an effective practice to promote health of both
babies and mothers.
</P>
<P>
"Preserving breast-feeding where it is the practice, restoring
it where it is not, and creating an environment that enables
mothers and babies to breast-feed merit the unreserved support of
every community and all its members," said WHO Director-General
Hiroshi Nakajima in a statement on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The WHO chief's statement was issued to endorse World
Breast-feeding Week on August 1-7, an annual awareness-raising
event organized by the World Alliance for Breast-feeding Action, a
nongovernmental organization spanning all continents.
</P>
<P>
The theme of this year's event is "Breast-feeding: a Community
Responsibility".
</P>
<P>
According to WHO studies, human milk is a living substance of
great biological complexity that not only provides unique
protection against infectious disease, but also stimulates the
baby's own immune system.
</P>
<P>
When babies are artificially fed the most immediately apparent
result is increased rates of sickness and death, the WHO says.
Moreover, artificial feeding can do no more than approximate the
physiological and emotional significance of the act of
breast-feeding for babies and mothers alike.
</P>
<P>
Breast-feeding also protects a mother's health by reducing the
risk of after-birth bleeding when sucking starts within the first
hour, by helping to protect against ovarian cancer, and by
reducing the risk of anaemia.
</P>
<P>
The WHO also stressed that the length of time and the way
breast-feeding proceeds is also significant, once again for mother
and child alike.
</P>
<P>
For example, exclusive breast-feeding, that is, giving no other
fluid or food than breast milk to a baby, provides more than 98
percent protection from pregnancy during the first six months
after birth.
</P>
<P>
Studies also show that six months of exclusive breast-feeding
provides measurable protection against eczema and food intolerance
in children whose families have a history of allergic disease.
</P>
<P>
"All mother should be enabled to practise exclusive
breast-feeding and all babies should be fed exclusively on breast
milk from birth to four to six months of age", advised Nakajima in
his message.
</P>
<P>
"Thereafter, children should continue to be breast-fed, while
receiving appropriate and adequate complementary foods, for up to
two years of age and beyond," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Libya Attacks US Decision to Tighten Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Libya today attacked U.S. President
Bill Clinton for signing a new law tightening sanctions against
Libya and Iran, reports reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
Clinton signed a bill Monday to punish non-American companies
which invest annually 40 million U.S. dollars or more in energy
projects in Libya or Iran.
</P>
<P>
In its first comment on the bill, Libya's official news agency
JANA said that Clinton's decision reflects the failure of the
American anti-Libyan policy, which was opposed by allies of the
United States.
</P>
<P>
JANA said that the decision crystallizes selfish American
policy that harms interests of American people and their allies
and exposes America's bias towards Israel.
</P>
<P>
"The signing of this legislation cements American policy which
is based on narrow and selfish interests which have inflicted and
will eventually inflict damages on the American people's interests
in particular and the interests of the so-called allies in
general," the agency said.
</P>
<P>
The measure was an "exaggeration in the demonstration of hatred
and selfishness," it said, adding that the ban would backfire on
the United States.
</P>
<P>
Iran has also lashed out at Clinton's action, saying that the ban
was doomed to failure because the United States' allies have
rejected it.
</P>
<P>
Iran's Foreign Ministry's spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi said
Monday night that the American actions are against international
norms and laws on free global trade. 
</P>
