<HEADLINE> Iran Denies Existence of Terrorist Training Camp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Iran today strongly denied the
existence of any terrorist training camp inside the country in a
bid to avoid potential military attack by American forces.
</P>
<P>
The official statement was made by Iran's mission to the
United Nations in a communique which was published by the official
news agency IRNA.
</P>
<P>
The communique said "the Islamic Republic of Iran rejects in
the strongest possible terms the existence of any camp in Iran for
terrorist training."
</P>
<P>
Western diplomats here analyzed that if the United States
decides to launch military attack against Iran, there will be
three main targets.
</P>
<P>
The first target will be the Bushehr Nuclear Power plant
in the Persian Gulf because the United States and Israel are
accusing Iran of developing mass destruction weapons.
</P>
<P>
The other two targets would be training camps -- one in
northern Tehran and the other near the religious city of Qum, 156
kilometers south of the capital city of Tehran.
</P>
<P>
However, the communique noted, Iran's strength "lies not in
training any terrorists or supporting international terrorism" but
in its "unwavering commitment to the principle of rejecting both
hegemony and hegemonization."
</P>
<P>
The communique rejected USA Today's allegation about the
existence of terrorist camps in Iran, noting the paper "echoes
the disinformation campaign by Israeli secret service and the
desperate attempts by an Iranian terrorist organization in
Iraq."
</P>
<P>
It added, the victimization of Iran in public opinion by
"irresponsible and politically motivated propaganda" will more
than likely continue so long as "Iran refuses to surrender to
American pressure and hegemony." 
</P>
</TEXT>
