<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Objects to U.S. Sanctions against Iran, Libya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Foreign Affairs Minister
Lloyd Axworthy and Minister for International Trade Art Eggleton
expressed Tuesday their strong objection to the U.S. sanctions
against foreign companies that invest in Iran and Libya.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, U.S. President Bill Clinton signed into law the
"Iran and Libya Sanctions Act of 1996", which will impose
sanctions on foreign firms that invest more than 40 million U.S.
dollars a year in Iran's and Libya's energy sector.
</P>
<P>
Under the law, Clinton has the option of denying foreign
businesses loans under the Export-Import Bank, banning their
imports, barring U.S. banks from making loans of more than 10
million U.S. dollars to uncooperative firms, and barring them from
bidding on U.S. government contracts.
</P>
<P>
"As with the Helms-Burton law, Canada continues to object to
unilateral measures that have extraterritorial effects; this
legislation is an inappropriate response to U.S. concerns," said
Axworthy in a statement issued here today.
</P>
<P>
"The extraterritorial effects of this latest act represent once
again an attempt by the United States to dictate trade policy to
its allies," he said, adding that Canada will continue to "defend
its interests against the extraterritorial application of such
legislation."
</P>
<P>
This latest U.S. move has already aroused strong opposition
from the 15-nation European Union and other countries.
</P>
<P>
Canada would be consulting on this matter with the EU and other
allies to determine how best to address the extraterritorial
impact of the act, indicated Axworthy and Eggleton.
</P>
<P>
Although Canadian investment in Iran and Libya is very limited
and its firms are unlikely to be affected by the U.S. act, the
Canadian government has voiced its strong opposition, viewing it
as a further indication of the U.S. willingness to impose its laws
beyond its borders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
