<HEADLINE> June Sees Biggest Fall in UK Industrial Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- British industrial output fell
unexpectedly in June as the manufacturing sector continued to
struggle, fueling suspicion of another cut in UK interest rates.
</P>
<P>
According to figures released Monday by the Office for National
Statistics (ONS), total industrial production, which includes
factory output, oil and gas extraction and energy production, fell
by 1.1 percent in June, compared with a rise of 0.8 percent in
May. It was the biggest monthly drop since November 1992.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturing output in June fell 0.3 percent, and 0.5 percent
year-on-year, its lowest level since June 1993. It has failed to
grow for three successive quarters.
</P>
<P>
The decline went against both City expectations of a small rise
in output and more optimistic evidence from recent industrial
trends surveys.
</P>
<P>
Industrial output failed to grow in the three months to June
compared with the same period a year ago, said the ONS.
</P>
<P>
The statistics office estimated for the seventh successive
month that output would remain flat in both total industrial
production and manufacturing industries, with energy production
depressed by the warm weather and activity in the North Sea
constrained by maintenance work.
</P>
<P>
Economists believe that with political pressures weighing
heavily on Chancellor of the Exchequer Kenneth Clarke's mind, the
latest figures may offer him useful ammunition to argue for
another interest rate cut in autumn. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
