<HEADLINE> Wildlife Protection in Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, Augest 7 (Xinhua) -- Natural reserves and wildlife
protection are being improved in China's northwest, home of rare
species such as golden monkey and crested ibis.
</P>
<P>
According to a newly-published research report, there are more
than 230 rare species under key state protection in Shaanxi,
Gansu, and Qinghai provinces and the Ningxia Hui and Xinjiang
Uygur Autonomous regions.
</P>
<P>
Ma Naixi says that 69 nature reserves have been established,
covering 5.3 percent of the total area of this region.
</P>
<P>
According to Ma, who is director of the Center for Chinese
Natural Reserve Studies at Northwest University in Xi'an, the
nature reserves are the main way of protecting wildlife in such
an ecologically-unstable region.
</P>
<P>
In Foping Nature Reserve in Shaanxi Province, the number of
giant panda has increased from less than 100 to more than 200
since it was established.
</P>
<P>
In Yangxian County in Shaanxi, seven crested ibis, one of the
world's rarest species, were discovered in 1981, just after a
special protection zone was set up. The bird's numbers have now
increased to some 50, and artificial propagation has scored some
success.
</P>
<P>
Similar stories can be found in the protection of wild
horses and other animals.
</P>
<P>
According to authorities, a plan that involves more government
efforts and more participation from local people will be drawn up
to raise wildlife protection in this region to a new level.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
