<HEADLINE> Italian Businessmen Criticize U.S. Sanction Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Italian businessmen have expressed
strong reactions against the United States law threatening to
punish foreign companies with business links with Iran and
Libya. They clam, the measures will affect Italy's economic
interests.
</P>
<P>
Under the so-called d' Amato Law, signed by U.S. President Bill
Clinton on Monday, any foreign companies or individuals who invest
more than 40 million U.S. dollars in the energy section in Iran
and Libya will be punished by the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
Most of the local newspapers today published the reaction of
the businessmen in front pages and some newspapers even set aside
special pages and columns for the reactions.
</P>
<P>
The strongest came from such enterprises as Group Eni and Fiat,
which have close investments and trade relations with companies
of Iran and Libya.
</P>
<P>
Italian companies could be among those most at risk as Iran and
Libya provide almost 45 percent of the 85 million tons of oil
imported annually by the country.
</P>
<P>
About 24 million tons are imported from Libya by Eni, Italy's
partially privatized oil company, through its production and
exploration subsidiary Agip, which has a significant natural gas
investment in Libya.
</P>
<P>
The total trade volume between Italy and Libya was 7.656
trillion liras (5 billion U.S. dollars) in 1995, and the volume
between Italy and Iran was 3,701 billion lira (2.4 billion
dollars).
</P>
<P>
A senior businessman in Eni said the U.S. sanctions against
Libya and Iran was a political issue, but it affected the economic
interests of the companies of other countries.
</P>
<P>
The businessmen asked the Italian government to protect the
economic interests of companies affected by the law.
</P>
<P>
The local media said the United States should not isolate one
country today and punish another country the next because that not
only affected the economic interests of other countries but also
made people nervous.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini said his government would fight
against international terrorism as always, but hoped that when the
United States imposed sanctions against other countries it would
take into consideration the economic interests of its allies.
</P>
<P>
The Italian government would try its best to protect Italian
companies' economic interests abroad, Dini said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
