<HEADLINE> Foreign Trade Down in Guangdong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The volume of imports and
exports in south China's Guangdong Province topped 47.4 billion US
dollars in the first half of the year, down 3.2 percent from the
same period of 1995, local customs officials said today.
</P>
<P>
The province's foreign trade accounts for 37.3 percent of the
country's total. Exports dropped by 7.4 percent to 25.1 billion US
dollars, and imports rose by two percent to 22.3 billion US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Both slowing down, with exports decreasing slightly since March
and imports dropping gradually in May and June after a sharp rise
in January and February, and a slighter rise in March and April.
</P>
<P>
Exports of ordinary commodities are seeing a dramatic decrease,
with volume dropping by 50.5 percent in the first six months of
the year.
</P>
<P>
Imports of ordinary commodities rose by 22.8 percent, due to
the reduction in import duties and some imports halted.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is still the province's biggest business partner,
while Japan, the US, Taiwan, the Republic of Korea, Germany, and
Singapore are other major business partners.
</P>
<P>
Traditional exports of clothing, shoes, textiles and toys are
declining, while imports of rolled steel, paper, paperboard and
other major items increased. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
