<HEADLINE> Mubarak: Syria, Israel Differ on Basis of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
said today that there is a gap between Syria and Israel on the
basis of peace negotiations though both sides are willing to
resume their talks.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference following his meeting with visiting
Syrian President Hafez al-Assad in the Egyptian Mediterranean port
city of Alexandria, Mubarak expressed hope that the two sides
would reach some sort of compromise to resume their negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The meeting came amid hopes that the Syrian-Israeli talks may
be resumed soon.
</P>
<P>
Al-Assad, who arrived in Alexandria earlier today, told the joint
press conference with Mubarak that the peace process should
continue to be based on the terms of reference of the 1991 Madrid
peace conference, Security Council resolutions and the
land-for-peace principle.
</P>
<P>
"We heard that the Israeli premier has asked Syria to resume
the talks but he did not mention any formula that indicates hopes
in peace prospects," he said.
</P>
<P>
Replying a question on the so-called "Lebanon first" proposal
put forward by Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, al-Assad
said that it should be "Lebanon and Syria first."
</P>
<P>
"Syria and Lebanon are taking the same steps," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Netanyahu's proposal, Israel will pull out its
troops from the Israeli self-styled "security zone" in south Lebanon
in exchange for Syria's help in disarming the Lebanese pro-Iranian
Hezbollah guerillas and ensuring security on Israel's northern
border with Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
But both Lebanon and Syria have rejected the proposal. During
their talks in Damascus Monday, al-Assad and Lebanese President Elias
Hrawi agreed to adopt a common stand on the peace moves with
Israel.
</P>
<P>
At today's press conference broadcast live by the Egyptian
television, al-Assad expressed hope that peace would be achieved as
soon as possible, adding that it would be for all parties and not
for one party in particular.
</P>
<P>
Both Mubarak and al-Assad stressed that all agreements Israel
signed with the Arabs should be implemented.
</P>
<P>
Today's meeting was the latest of a series of recent
consultations between Arab leaders to explore ways to revive the
stalled Arab-Israeli peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Al-Assad met with Jordan's King Hussein last Saturday and then
held talks Monday with Hrawi to coordinate their stances on the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, the first Arab state to make peace with Israel in 1979,
has been playing an active role in pushing forward the Middle East
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Al-Assad left Alexandria following the news conference, ending his
brief visit to Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
