<HEADLINE> 1,600 VMs Removed from Whitehead Detention Center in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 7 (Xinhua) -- An operation to remove about
1,600 Vietnamese migrants (VMs) from the Whitehead Detention
Center (WHDC) was completed here today, said a spokesman for the
Hong Kong Correctional Services Department (CSD).
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that the operation was to remove 656 VMs to
Victoria Prison pending their repatriation to Vietnam and the
transfer of about 950 VMs to the High Island Detention Center
(HIDC).
</P>
<P>
He said that the operation encountered some delay this morning
when some VMs staged passive resistance to the operation.
</P>
<P>
He said that at the beginning, the operation went on smoothly
with some 900 VMs packing up their belongings for the trips to
Victoria Prison and HIDC, but about mid-day, the process came to a
halt when 653 VMs staged a sit-in in their dormitories and refused
to cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He said that a total of 126 VMs were physically escorted out,
78 were carried out and three were restrained with plastic
handcuffs and removed, while the rest of the VMs left the camp of
their own accord.
</P>
<P>
Three CSD staff sustained minor injuries during today's
operation and a police officer was slightly hurt when he was hit
by a stone from a Vietnamese migrant, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, the 656 VMs transferred to Victoria
 Prison will receive medical checks and have pre-flight
documentation before they will be repatriated to Vietnam on August
 12, 15 and 22.  
</P>
</TEXT>
