<HEADLINE> Israel: No Comment on New US Sanction Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 7 (Xinhua) -- A senior Israeli official
today declined to comment on a new U.S. law that will punish
foreign businesses that invest in the oil sectors in Iran and
Libya.
</P>
<P>
Moshe Fogel, director of the Government Press Office, told
Xinhua that the legislation was "an issue for the U.S. government,"
and Israel would not comment on the U.S. move.
</P>
<P>
"However," Fogel said, "we, in Israel, do believe that Iran
has been involved in supporting and encouraging terrorism in the
Middle East and around the world."
</P>
<P>
Fogel also expressed his belief that the international
community should cooperate and make joint efforts in fighting
against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, U.S. President Bill Clinton signed a bill
imposing sanctions against foreign companies with substantial
investments in the petroleum industries of Iran and Libya.
</P>
<P>
In signing the new law, Clinton promised to "continue to
press" American allies "to join with us in increasing the
pressure on Iran and Libya to stop their support for terrorists."
</P>
<P>
However, the U.S. decision has drawn sharp criticism from
France and other European countries which believed that the move
went against the principles of the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
A French Foreign Ministry spokesman said that it would "create
a particularly dangerous precedent for the security and the
development of commerce."
</P>
<P>
He said France would work together with the European Union to
protect any French companies from being hurt by the law. 
</P>
