<HEADLINE> Rebels Continue Assault on Chechen Compound </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Chechen rebels continued their
fierce attacks on the compound of the pro-Moscow government in the
regional capital of Grozny during Wednesday daytime.
</P>
<P>
Itar-Tass news agency said the separatist fighters, who had
blockaded the compound, fired grenade launchers at Russian
positions protecting it and one building was already on fire.
</P>
<P>
But the rebels had so far failed to capture the complex, which
included the office of the Russian government's representative to
Chechnya, and a hotel.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of Russian journalists, medical and construction workers
have been holed up in the complex since Tuesday when the rebels
began their lightning offensive against Grozny, the fiercest in
five months.
</P>
<P>
In an earlier report, Itar-Tass said a column of Russian
armored vehicles was moving toward central Grozny from Khankala, a
Russian military base just outside the capital city.
</P>
<P>
A Russian official in Chechnya said Russian troops were working
on a plan to oust the rebels from Grozny and commandos had been
sent to reinforce Russian troops there.
</P>
<P>
Russian Deputy Interior Minister Pavel Golubets said 29 Russian
soldiers had been killed and 100 others wounded since the rebels
staged their assaults on Grozny Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
He said casualty figures for the rebels were "two to three
times higher." But the rebels claimed they only had five dead and
10 injured.
</P>
<P>
Rebel spokesman Movladi Udugov told Russian Television that the
raid was in retaliation for a month of Russian bombardments of
their villages and strongholds in the southern mountains.
</P>
<P>
Russian officials estimated there were about 500 to 700 rebels
operating in Grozny, but the Chechen government estimated there
were 2,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
