<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Plans Tax Increase For Foreign Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 7 (Xinhua) -- China plans to raise the income
tax on foreign banks before they get involved in the local
currency business on a trial basis this year, according to an
official source.
</P>
<P>
"To cope with the needs of doing business in yuan by overseas
banks, government departments are planning interim measures for
the selected banks and to raise their income tax rate," the source
said.
</P>
<P>
Differences in the income tax level of domestic and foreign
banks have long been a barrier to doing business in yuan, he said,
noting that the income tax rate at present is 55 percent for
Chinese banks, 15 percent for overseas banks in China's special
economic zones, and 33 percent for other foreign banks.
</P>
<P>
"On the one hand, tax privileges for foreign banks should not
be retained after they are allowed to deal in the local currency,"
the official source said. "On the other, it is also improper to
withdraw all tax privileges for foreign banks, because conditions
for an across-the-board opening of the yuan business are not quite
mature."
</P>
<P>
A proper solution will be canceling the income tax privileges
for foreign banks and setting a "reasonable tax rate acceptable to
all sides" so as to meet the needs of experimenting with the yuan
business by overseas banks, the official said.
</P>
<P>
All foreign banks will be taxed at the same rate after the
period of experimentation is over and foreign banks are allowed to
do full-scale business with yuan, the official source said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mt. Wutai Attracts More Tourists in Summer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Since June, over 200,000 Chinese
and overseas tourists and pilgrims have visited Mount Wutai, one
of the four sacred Buddhist shrines in China, drawn by both the
relics and the cool environment.
</P>
<P>
The popular spot in north China's Shanxi Province has seen a
more than 10 percent increase of tourists in the past two months.
</P>
<P>
Local officials believe that the tourist season this year will
be half a year rather than the usual three to four months. The
mountain's hotels are usually packed in summer and empty in winter.
</P>
<P>
Officials attribute the summer boom to efforts to attract
tourists, with seven new tourist routes that combine relics with
natural beauty being offered.
</P>
<P>
The increase is also due to a new weekend tour designed for
people from neighboring provinces.
</P>
<P>
At 3,058 meters, Mt. Wutai is the highest peak in north
China. The other three Buddhist shrines that enjoy equal
popularity are Emei Mountain in Sichuan, Jiuhua Mountain in Anhui
and Putuo Mountain in Zhejiang.
</P>
<P>
"With the new routes, tourists not only see Buddhist rituals in
more than 100 temples and enjoy the natural beauty of the
mountain, but also entertain themselves in more than 20 new
Karaoke halls and have spring-water baths and a massage in modern
hotels," an official at Mt. Wutai said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No World Record Set at Sestriere Track Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 7 (Xinhua) -- A 150,000-dollar Ferrari sports car
went unclaimed Wednesday as rusty heroes from Atlanta failed to
shatter any world record at Europe's highest track and field meet
held in Sestriere, Italy.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time in three years that the top prize on the
line for the athlete setting a world record was not awarded,
though high altitude in Sestriere was expected to help world
record attempts by sprinters and jumpers.
</P>
<P>
In the men's 100-meter dash, Canada's Bruny Surin won in a time
of 10.17 seconds with Linford Christie of Britain second in 10.29
and Nigerian Osmond Ezinwa third in 10.30.
</P>
<P>
America's Olympic 110-meter hurdles champion Allen Johnson
confirmed his superiority in the event by easily beating veteran
compatriot 1984 Olympic champion Roger Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Britain's Colin Jackson, the former World champion but only
fourth in the Olympic final, again disappointed to run third.
</P>
<P>
Jonathan Edwards, Britain's triple jump world record holder,
gained some compensation for his silver medal in Atlanta by
winning the event here. His jump of 17.67 meters saw off Brian
Wellman of Bermuda who jumped 17.53 meters.
</P>
<P>
In a repeat of the Olympic final, gold medalist Randy Barnes
beat fellow American and silver medalist John Godina in the men's
shot put, with a throw of 21.65 meters.
</P>
<P>
Scott Huffman and Joe Greene led 1-2 triumphs by U.S. athletes
in the pole vault and long jump.
</P>
<P>
Greene had the fifth best world performance this year as he
jumped 8.46 meters, with the wind blowing barely within the
allowed 2 meters per second.
</P>
<P>
Erick Walder finished second with a leap of 8.35.
</P>
<P>
Rosie Edeh scored another Canadian victory in the women's
400-meter hurdles, in 54.97 seconds, ahead of Ireland's Susan
Smith.
</P>
<P>
Zambian Samuel Matete, a silver medalist in Atlanta, captured
the men's 400-meter hurdles in 49.03 seconds. Ken Harnden of
Zimbabwe placed second in 50.24.
</P>
<P>
Jamaican sprinter Merlene Ottey, a double silver medalist in
Atlanta, limped out of the women's 100 meters following a light
thigh strain suffered during the warmup.
</P>
<P>
Luke Kipkosgei led a Kenyan sweep of the top five places in the
men's 3,000 meters, the only long distance race in the program.
</P>
</TEXT>
