<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 14:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkish Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister
Tansu Ciller has said that Turkey will speed up the crawling pace
of its privatization program, according to the local newspaper
Daily News today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Ciller as saying that preparations have been
accelerated to privatize Turkey's mining concern Etibank and its
telecommunications company Turk Telecom as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The Japanese Export-Import Bank will extend a
600 million Saudi riyals (160 million U.S. dollars) loan to Saudi
Arabia under an agreement newly signed with Saudi Methanol Company
to reinforce the facilities of the company.
</P>
<P>
This is the first direct investment loan that the Export-Import
Bank of Japan has ever made to the kingdom, according to Tuesday's
Saudi Arabian English-language daily Arab News.
</P>
<P>
The loan will be used to reinforce the facilities at which the
company produces methanol from natural gas supplied by Saudi
Aramco, the largest Saudi state-owned company dealing with oil,
through the technology provided by Mitsubishi Gas Chemical
Corporation.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran has announced a total of 11 oil and gas key
projects, worth at least 7 billion U.S. dollars, for bidding in
defiance of the U.S. government's toughened sanctions against
Iran. according to Iranian oil industry sources today.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that more than 120 foreign oil and gas companies
have offered their bids in the Iranian oil and gas sector.
</P>
<P>
They said that the latest sanctions imposed by the United
States on Iran will have neither short-term nor long-term impact on
the country's oil and gas sector.
</P>
<P>
The oil industry is the pillar of Iran's economy. Iran earns
about 14 to 16 billion U.S. dollars by exporting crude oil and the
oil export revenue accounts for about 70 percent of the total
export income of the country.
</P>
<P>
Cairo -- Egyptian Minister of Supply and Foreign Trade Ahmed
Goweili has issued a resolution to allow cotton to be stored for
more than one month, the local English-language newspaper The
Egyptian Gazette reported today.
</P>
<P>
Goweili said that this is part of the government's policy,
which is aimed at removing all obstacles to free cotton export and
import. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
