<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan, Turkmenistan Discuss Pipeline Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Turkmen Deputy Prime
Minister Boris Shikhmuradov held talks here today with Pakistani
Minister for Petroleum and Natural Resources Saifullah Khan on the
proposed gas and crude oil pipelines projects.
</P>
<P>
According to a Turkmen official, the Turkmen government will
soon announce the formation of consortium for undertaking these
projects, .
</P>
<P>
Shikhmuradov, who is also foreign minister, said that
Turkmenistan was keen to develop economic relations with Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Turkmen Oil Minister Gochmurad Nazdjanov, who is with
Shikhmuradov on the visit here, said that gas reserves of
Sovietabad-Daulatabad gas fields located at 110 Kilometer away
from the Afghan border have been dedicated for this pipeline.
</P>
<P>
The reserves have been estimated at 45 trillion cubic feet
(TCF) and have already been certified, Mazdjanov said.
</P>
<P>
Saifullah said the Pakistani government was very keen to get
these projects completed as early as possible as both, gas and
crude oil pipelines would usher a new era of prosperity in the
region.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani minister said the projects would provide an
alternate economically viable outlet to Turkmen resources.
</P>
<P>
A few foreign companies operating in Pakistan in the petroleum
sector had also shown their interest in these projects and they
were expected to join the consortium, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
