<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tourists Visiting Three Gorges Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, August 7 (Xinhua) -- More than 60,000 overseas
tourists visited the Three Gorges on the Yangtze River during the
first six months of this year, according to statistics, an
increase of 50 percent over last year.
</P>
<P>
Although the number of tourists is usually down in July and
August, this year is expected to see continued growth in the
number of tourist ship guests.
</P>
<P>
Yangtze River's largest tourist ship company had over 6,000
customers in July.
</P>
<P>
Tourist officials estimate that the river, which is the longest
in China, will have a record number of tourists this year.
</P>
<P>
"This is because many people from overseas, like many Chinese,
want to see the Three Gorges before many of the scenic spots are
submerged by the huge dam," an official explained.
</P>
<P>
To pave the way for construction of the 185-meter-high dam, the
river will be dammed and the course will be changed next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> American Specialists Arrive in Saudi Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 7 (Xinhua)-- The first batch of a 1,200
American specialists team has arrived in Saudi Arabia to help
moving 4,000 U.S.troops from towns to more isolated remote base to
make them less vulnerable to terrorist attacks.
</P>
<P>
According to Kuwait New Agency (KUNA), the troops would be
moved from Air bases at Saudi capital Riyadh and Dhahran to the
Prince Sultan Air Base at Al-Kharj, about 70 kilometers south of
Riyadh.
</P>
<P>
Five U.S. soldiers were killed in Riyadh on November 13 last
year when a car bomb exploded in the parking lot of a Saudi
Arabian National Guard Training Center while 19 airmen were
killed and several hundred others injured in a truck bomb blast on
June 25 in a U.S. Air Force dormitory area of a Saudi air base at
Dhahran.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Saudi Arabia reached an agreement during a
two-day visit by the U.S. Defense Minister William Perry to the
kingdom late last month which decided that 4,000 U.S. troops in
Saudi Arabia would be relocated to ensure their safety against
terrorists attacks. Saudi Arabia is host of 5,000 U.S. troops
under task of protecting Gulf security.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the 1,200 specialists team consists of 300
engineers, 200 security police and 100 combat communications
personnel. Others would be air traffic controllers, weather
forecasters, fuel handlers and maintenance workers.
</P>
<P>
The movement work is expected to be completed within
several weeks.
</P>
<P>
During stages of the troops movement, the U.S. military would
supply internal security while the Saudis would provide external
security, it is understood.
</P>
<P>
Americans in Saudi Arabia have been on a very high state
of alert following the two bomb blasts.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, it is learnt that plans of
sending families of American troops in the kingdom back home
are also under review.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
