<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liaoning Developing Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Liaoning, a renowned, old heavy
industrial center in northeast China, is striving to develop new
technology for transforming outmoded, traditional industries.
</P>
<P>
Key targets are computers and software, biological medicine,
new materials, refined chemistry, integration of electronics and
machinery, and modern telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
The province plans to raise its output value from high
technology production to 50 billion yuan by the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1995, Liaoning had invested 520 million yuan in
developing 400 new high-tech products. Production of multi-media
computers, robots, and electrostatic technology is now in place.
</P>
<P>
New high-tech development zones will be built in the next few
years to serve these ends.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Foreign Funds For Qingdao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Qingdao, one of the country's open
coastal cities, in east China's Shandong province, has become a
favorite place for foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
Eight major international corporations had combined contractual
investment of 150 million US dollars in the city between December
of last year and May this year.
</P>
<P>
Qingdao's High-tech Industrial Zone, Economic and Technology
Development Zone, Bonded Zone, and the Shilaoren (Stone Old Man)
National Tourism and Holiday Resort Zone have so far attracted
more than 1,500 overseas-funded enterprises. Moreover, the city
has developed a number of brand-name products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
