<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 12:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti MPs Call for Measures to Curb Visa Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Kuwaiti National Assembly
has called for effective measures to curb visa trading in the
country, official sources said today.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the parliamentarians agreed Tuesday night to
refer to the government a report made by a parliamentary committee
charged with evaluating government measures in fighting visa
trading.
</P>
<P>
The sources added that the report falls short of spelling out
clear measures to fight this growing phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
The committee set up earlier this year made several
recommendations urging the Kuwaiti government to continue
tightening the restrictions on all violators and intensify
inspection campaigns on commercial sites to book violators, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
It also recommended reevaluation of granting visit visas to
close the door on those who enter the country under the pretext of
visit.
</P>
<P>
But it is learned that the deputies described the report as
inconclusive and indecisive which attributes the visa-trading
problem to the period after Kuwait's liberation from the Iraqi
seven-month occupation in 1991 when tens of thousands of foreign
workers entered the country.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the deputies decided to refer the report to
the government without making any decision following a heated
debate on the issue.
</P>
<P>
During the debate, the MPs criticized the government for being
unable to check the influx of expatriate manpower into the
country.
</P>
<P>
They stressed the fact that most of them are unskilled laborers
who entered the country with illegal visas they had bought from
Kuwaiti sponsors. One deputy cited the price of visas at 2,310
U.S. dollars each.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaitis accounted for 38 percent of the total population last
year, and the figure declined to 36 percent this year with the
Kuwaiti work force registered only 16.5 percent, the deputies
said.
</P>
<P>
They described this trend as contradicting the government plan
in which the Kuwaiti citizens will account for 50 percent of the
population by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
One deputy said if the situation continues, Kuwaitis will be a
minority in the country.
</P>
<P>
One parliamentarian accused some members of the ruling family
of trading visas, but Interior Minister Ali Al-Sabah categorically
denied the charge, challenging him to present evidence to support
his claim.
</P>
<P>
While criticizing the government for inefficiency in curbing
visa trading, the deputies also pointed out that many laborers,
out of fear of being deported, refused to cooperate-operate with
the authorities in providing information on visa traders.
</P>
<P>
However, the Kuwaiti government strongly denied the deputies'
accusations, saying it is taking swift measures to tackle the
problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
