<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anomalous Astronomical Phenomena Predict Largest Earthquake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 7 (Xinhua) -- A series of abnormal celestial
phenomena foretold the earthquake that claimed 240,000 lives in
Tangshan, in northern China, in 1976, but the omens were ignored,
according two geologists.
</P>
<P>
In a lecture at the 30th International Geological Congress, Xu
Daoyi and Du Pinren of the Institute of Geology of the State
Seismological Bureau said that there have been serious earthquakes
in the eastern part of north China every 22 years, a cycle that
coincides perfectly with the magnetism of sunspots.
</P>
<P>
The conclusion is supported by earthquake records since 1888,
when a quake hit the Bohai Sea area.
</P>
<P>
According to the scientists, most earthquakes near Tangshan
occur with monthly tidal high points. On July 28, 1976, the
largest tide was observed in Tanggu Harbor near Tangshan about 16
minutes prior to the earthquake.
</P>
<P>
A meteor shower in Jilin province, northeast China, four months
before the quake suggested an inauspicious future. The meteorites'
remains covered a 500-square-meter area and weighed a total of
three tons. east China's Shandong province and northeast China's
Liaoning province were also hit by aerolites at that time.
</P>
<P>
Both Xu and Du held that historic records show that a meteorite
shower always accompanied a strong earthquake.
</P>
<P>
The earthquake is not only a result of kinetic and thermal
changes in the earth's inner part, but also caused by astronomic
movements, Xu said The vicissitudes in sunspots and tides will
be the main force triggering a strong quake.
</P>
<P>
He and his colleagues also suggest that astronomy be used in
earthquake research as a new way of looking at how earthquakes
occur.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
