<HEADLINE> American Activists Defy US Ban on Travel to Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Three Americans headed for Iraq
via Jordan Monday carrying medicines for Iraqi children for the
third time in open defiance of the U.N. sanctions and an American
ban on travel by U.S. citizens to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Kathy Kelly, Bradford Lyttle and Richard McDowell, members of
a group called Voices in the Wilderness, are carrying medicines
worth 8,000 U.S. dollars to be delivered to Iraqi hospitals.
</P>
<P>
The three activists risk up to 12 years of imprisonment and/or
a 1-million-dollar-fine for violating the sanctions and the
U.S. ban, but publicly challenging the U.S. policy towards Iraq,
according to today's English-language daily Jordan Times.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that one of the most powerful protests that we
can make against the sanctions is to publicly break them by
taking urgently needed medical supplies to Iraq," said a
statement released by the group, quoted by the daily.
</P>
<P>
"The penalty for breaking the sanctions in this way can be
12 years in prison and/or up to 1 million dollars in fine,"
said the statement.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that this is a small price to pay if it
can prevent the death of even one Iraqi child," it added.
</P>
<P>
The group delivered similar supplies to a hospital in Baghdad
in March 1996 in a much publicized event.
</P>
<P>
Food and medicine are exempt from the U.N. sanctions against
Iraq, but all deliveries should have prior approval from the
U.N. Sanctions Committee.
</P>
<P>
Those without such approval are technically considered as a
violation of the six-year-old embargo.
</P>
<P>
The group said its members have already received warning
letters from the Clinton Administration but they ignored them.
</P>
<P>
Kelly said most American people remain unaware of the "tragic
affliction that continues in Iraq."
</P>
<P>
"Many genuinely concerned people mistakenly believe that these
cruel sanctions (against Iraq) have been at least partially
lifted, but, in fact, the U.S. has blocked that U.N.-sponsored
efforts," she added.
</P>
<P>
The three-member mission to Iraq will reportedly hold press
conferences and give television interviews while in Baghdad before
returning to Jordan on August 15.
</P>
<P>
They will also visit the offices of the United Nations
Development Fund in Amman to deliver a letter to the U.N.
reaffirming their opposition to the sanctions against Iraq,
according to the daily.
</P>
<P>
They are also expected to visit the U.S. embassy here in
Amman to "announce the delivery of supplies to Iraq," the
daily reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
