<HEADLINE> Syrian, Egyptian Presidents Meet to Discuss Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Syrian President Hafez al-Assad
is meeting Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak in the Egyptian port
city of Alexandria to discuss ways of reviving the Middle East
peace process and getting it resumed on all tracks of negotiation
with Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian-Egyptian summit comes within intensified contacts
currently seen by the Arab states.
</P>
<P>
During the summit, the Egyptian President will brief his Syrian
counterpart on the outcome of his recent talks and contacts with
U.S. President Bill Clinton and other American officials on ways
of resuming the Middle East peace negotiations, especially after
Syria has officially turned down the "Lebanon First" proposal put
forward by Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Natanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Syria considered the "Lebanon First" proposal a trap intended
to keep the Syria track of peace talks with Israel away from the
Lebanese one, on the grounds that the status of the occupied
Syrian Golan Heights is more difficult and more complicated, in
addition to the fact that Israel is seeking to make of Lebanon a
meeting-point with Syria.
</P>
<P>
Syria had informed Jordanian King Hussein of its rejection of
the "Lebanon First" proposal.
</P>
<P>
According to diplomatic sources in the Syrian capital, the
efforts made by the U.S. through the contacts by its Secretary of
State Warren Christopher and coordinator of the Middle East peace
process Dennis Ross with both Syria and Israel have not succeeded
in persuading the two sides to resume the peace negotiations
between them.
</P>
<P>
By holding meetings with Arab leaders, Syria is seeking to
unify and coordinate the Arab attitudes toward the Israeli
"Lebanon First" proposal.
</P>
<P>
Syria is also seeking to freeze the dialogue and relations
between Israel and Arab states, linking these relations with
securing some progress in the peace process, and getting the
recent resolutions adopted at the Cairo Arab summit held in June
implemented. 
</P>
</TEXT>
