<HEADLINE> French Minister: No Lesson to Learn from U.S. on Terrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- French Delegate-Minister for
European Affairs Michel Barnier said today that France has no
lesson to learn from the United States on terrorism.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the France-Inter radio today, Barnier said
that France considers this act by the U.S. as a unilateral decision.
"The Americans always intend to play the role of policeman in the
world. Can the world have only one policeman to combat terrorism?
Of course not," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think that one can effectively fight terrorism all
alone while taking solitary measures which could undermine
European enterprises," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said that France understands that U.S. President Bill
Clinton wants to appease public opinion at home and the congress,
"but I hope that considerations for interior politics will not
take away the necessary and obligatory solidarity (among Western
countries) in fighting terrorism."
</P>
<P>
The Group of Seven (G-7) most industrialized countries and
Russia adopted 25 measures last Tuesday in Paris to combat
terrorism, which did not include economic sanctions against Iran
and Libya.
</P>
<P>
Barnier said that these measures will prove effective in
fighting terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Clinton signed a congressional bill on Monday authorizing
sanctions against any foreign company or individual investing more
than 40 million dollars in energy section of Iran and Libya.
</P>
<P>
The legislation was known as d'Amato law in reference to its
main author, Republican Senator Alfonso d'Amato of New York.
</P>
