<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Fears U.S. Sanctions Law Could Hurt Oil Supply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission has voiced
deep concern that the U.S. legislation penalizing non-American
companies with business links with Iran and Libya would have
potentially serious implications for the security of energy
supplies to the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
Under the so-called D'Amato law, signed by U.S. President Bill
Clinton on Monday, the U.S. government will punish those foreign
companies or individuals that invest more than 40 million
U.S. dollars a year in the energy sectors of Iran and Libya.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the executive arm of the EU, warned on
Tuesday that 20 percent of EU oil imports came from the two
countries and the U.S. sanctions law could affect EU oil supplies,
according to report carried in today's Financial Times newspaper.
</P>
<P>
EU companies including France's Total and Elf, Repsol of Spain,
Petrofina of Belgium, Austria's OMV, and Germany's Veba and
Wintershall all have interests in one or both of the countries on
the U.S. sanctions list, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Italian companies could be among those most at risk as Iran and
Libya account for almost 44 percent of the 85 million tons of oil
imported annually by the country.
</P>
<P>
About 24 million tons are imported from Libya by Eni, Italy's
partially privatized oil company, through its production and
exploration subsidiary Agip, which has a significant natural gas
investment in Libya.
</P>
<P>
Agip produces an average of 110,000 barrels a day from its
Libyan oil fields and has plans to develop pipeline under the
Mediterranean to Italy.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts say the main issue appears to be whether funds
spent in Libya on maintaining existing investments are regarded as
"new" by the D'Amato legislation, thus restricting all such flows
to within the 40 million dollars annual limit.
</P>
<P>
There is also particular concern that the law could serve as a
precedent for future sanctions legislation, which is aimed at
curbing EU trade, the analysts added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 11:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Levy Shuns Cabinet Meetings as Tension with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Foreign Minister David
Levy shunned cabinet meetings today as the tension between Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and the minister continued.
</P>
<P>
Levy did not appear this morning at the meeting that Netanyahu
held with senior cabinet members. He also stayed away from the
weekly inner cabinet meeting held this afternoon to discuss the
situation in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The latest rivalry between the two arch rivals came into
limelight early this week as the local media exposed the breakdown
of contacts between them.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu apparently tried to ignore Levy, who has not been
informed of the recent diplomatic contacts undergone by the Prime
Minister's Office. The entourage accompanying Netanyahu on his
recent visits to Egypt and Jordan also excluded any officials
from the Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that the two had not met since early this month,
and a regular Sunday meeting in last week was also canceled.
Unconfirmed reports said that Levy, holing up in his Beit She'an
home, was considering to resign for the second time in two months.
</P>
<P>
Publicizing his rift with Levy, Netanyahu claimed his primacy
over the peace process in an interview with Channel 2 Television
on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
"Israel has only one prime minister," affirmed Netanyahu,
saying he was given a mandate through Israel's first direct
election to direct the peace negotiations. He offered Levy "a
partnership," but making clear that he would lead.
</P>
<P>
The immediate issue is whether Levy will head a steering
committee on negotiations with the Palestinians. Netanyahu
indicated that the head of this committee would be someone he
trusted, but he denied reports he had decided to give the position
to Cabinet Secretary Danny Nevah.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry officials also complained that there was an
intention to create a "mini-Foreign Ministry" headed by
Netanyahu's foreign policy adviser Dore Gold, who has been active
in conducting diplomatic contacts on the prime minister's behalf.
</P>
<P>
Levy has barely acted as the foreign minister in his two
months' office, despite the fact that he held the first meeting
with Palestinian National Authority President Yasser Arafat in
late July.
</P>
<P>
It is still unclear whether the latest Netanyahu-Levy rift
only centered on the peace process or something else. However,
this is the second crisis appeared in the relationship between
the two since the Likud government assumed power in June.
</P>
<P>
In early July, Levy created a crisis by publicly threatening
to resign in order to force Netanyahu to bring Likud veteran
Ariel Sharon into the cabinet. Netanyahu was strongly critical of
Levy's move, though he appointed on July 8 Sharon as Minister of
National Infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
The deep-seated rivalry between Netanyahu and Levy dates back
to 1993 when the former defeated Levy and other party veterans to
become the leader of then opposition Likud party.
</P>
<P>
Levy split from the Likud early this year and formed the new
Gesher party, citing Netanyahu was trying to implicate him over a
scandal involving Netanyahu's extra-marital affair. Levy also said
that the internal Likud electoral procedures were biased against
his supporters.
</P>
<P>
Under the mediation by Sharon, Netanyahu forged an alliance
with Levy and Tsomet party head Rafael Eitan in a joint-ticket
agreement, that helped him win the May 29 elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
