<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistani PM Stresses Need for Population Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister
Benazir Bhutto today urged the people of the nation to help the
government in its endeavors to arrest the rapid growth of
population.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in Peshawar, provincial capital of Northwest Frontier
Province, Benazir said any development initiative remained
infructuous in the face of the population growth.
</P>
<P>
The Prime Minister said that with the present speed, Pakistan's
population would touch the figure of 150 million by the year 2000
and would reach 500 million in 2060 which were alarming figures.
</P>
<P>
Comparing the population growth with that of Japan and Brazil,
she said that Pakistan was two and a half times smaller in
population than Japan in 1947, but now Pakistan was much bigger
than Japan in terms of population.
</P>
<P>
"Had we adopted the measure the government of Japan had
introduced, we would have been half the population of Japan. We
would have been a wheat exporting rather importing country and
would have achieved universal primary education target," Benazir
said.
</P>
<P>
She asked the Pakistani people to imagine as to what would be
the condition when the country's population reaches 150 million by
the year 2000, 230 million in 2020 and 500 million in 2060.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister, however, listed the steps taken by the
present government for controlling the population growth and said,
in 1988 the population growth was 3.1 percent while it had dropped
to 2.9 percent as a result of various government measures.
</P>
<P>
She assured that Pakistan's population growth would be lowered
to 2.6 percent during the next few years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
