<HEADLINE> Switzerland Joins Criticism Against New U.S. Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Swiss government on Tuesday
added its voice to the criticism of the U.S. sanctions law on Iran
and Libya, saying it always opposes such measures that have
extraterritorial power, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
"Switzerland always opposes the laws that have extraterritorial
effect because the country stands for the simple respect of
economic liberalism," said Yves Seydoux, spokesman of the Federal
Department of Public Economy.
</P>
<P>
However, Swiss officials said they did not know of any Swiss
company threatened by the new U.S. law.
</P>
<P>
Switzerland has a relatively low trade volume with both Iran
and Libya.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, Swiss exports to Iran totalled 204 million Swiss
francs, or about 170 million U.S. dollars, while its imports from
the country totaling 69.7 million francs.
</P>
<P>
In the same year, its exports to Libya were 82.4 million francs
while imports from the country, mainly petroleum products,
totaling 350 million francs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
