<HEADLINE> DPRK Estimates Latest Flooding Loss at $1.7 Billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK) said the latest flooding has caused 1.7
billion U.S. dollars loss to the country.
</P>
<P>
Calling it the "biggest floods" in a hundred years, a spokesman
for the Foreign Ministry said here today that the natural disaster
hit 117 cities and counties of eight provinces in late July.
</P>
<P>
It has "a serious impact on the livelihood of the people and
the development of the national economy and, especially, cause a
temporary food problem," the spokesman said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"The economic losses caused by floods are enormous," he
acknowledged, adding that the country needed humanitarian
assistance from the international community.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, the flooding in August 1995 caused
a damage of 15 billion U.S. dollars, reduced the national output
of paddy rice and maize by more than two million tons and washed
away about a million tons of rice in stock.
</P>
<P>
A year ago, he said, another hailstorm devastated 170,000
hectares of arable land and entailed the loss of more than one
million tons of grain in North and South Hwanghae Provinces.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman expressed gratitude to the relief materials
offered by the different countries in the world, international
organizations, public organizations and individuals.
</P>
<P>
"We need humanitarian assistance from the international
community," he said. 
</P>
