<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Commissioner Concerned Over U.S. Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Greece's European Union (EU)
Commissioner for Energy Christos Papoutsis expressed his "deep
concern" over the U.S. law aimed at imposing sanctions on
companies investing in oil and gas projects in Libya and Iran,
according to an Athens news agency report from Brussels today.
</P>
<P>
"I should like to express my deep concern over the d'Amato
Law. When it comes into force, it will create major problems for
the European oil industry," Papoutsis said.
</P>
<P>
"According to the information we have, the sanctions include
new investments and the supply of technical equipment, which means
the further development and exploitation of oil and natural gas
reserves will be affected," Papoutsis added.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner also pointed out that the EU imported 80
percent of its oil, of which 20 percent from Libya and Iran, while
oil imports covered only 50 percent of U.S. requirements, which
were mainly from Venezuela, Mexico, Saudi Arabia and Norway.
</P>
<P>
"We must not forget that the oil market is a world market.
Consequently, any action which affects the market should be taken
after international consultations. Any interruption of the oil
volumes coming into the world market from Libya and Iran would
have a backlash not only on prices but also on the volumes being
transacted. These two countries account for 10 percent of the
world oil market," Papoutsis went on to say.
</P>
<P>
Papoutsis stressed that the European Commission was in favor of
structured dialogue rather than trade "reprisals," particularly
when the latter were foreseen by national legislation with
international repercussions and application. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
