<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ship-building Orders Won by S. Korea Decline Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 7 (Xinhua) -- South Korean shipbuilders received
orders for 58 vessels weighing 2.11 million gross tons from
overseas during the first seven months of this year, down 39
percent from the same period last year, the Korea Shipbuilders
Association (KSA) said here today.
</P>
<P>
"The trend is expected to continue as long as foreign shipping
firms are reluctant to build new vessels because of trends that
suggest a global economic slowdown. So we cannot rule out the
possibility that the total orders this year will decline compared
with that last year," a KSA official said.
</P>
<P>
South Korea is the second largest shipbuilding country in the
world following Japan with the annual shipbuilding capacity of 8.5
million tons.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the country received orders for 194 ships weighing
7.13 million gross tons, up 11.9-percent increase from the 6.37
million gross tons recorded in 1994.
</P>
<P>
South Korea's backlog of orders, which is based on the gross
tonnage of ships, stood at 11.66 million tons at the end of July
this year, down 14.4 percent from a year earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
