<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak Holds Talks with Assad on Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
held talks with his Syrian counterpart Hafez al-Assad today on the
Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, which took place in the Egyptian Mediterranean
port city of Alexandria, had been expected to mainly deal with the
Syrian and Lebanese tracks of the peace process and Israel's
decision to restart construction of Jewish settlements in the
Palestinian territories of the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
The Arabs, particularly the Palestinians, have criticized
Israel's decision on settlements as an obstacle to peace and a
violation of agreements already reached between Israel and the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Al-Assad, who arrived in Alexandria earlier today and was
welcomed by Mubarak at the airport, is being accompanied on his
brief visit by Syrian Vice-President Abdul-Halim Khaddam and
Foreign Minister Farouq al-Shara.
</P>
<P>
Today's meeting, amid hopes that the Syrian-Israeli peace talks
may be resumed soon, came just four days after al-Assad met with
Jordan's King Hussein in Damascus Saturday to explore ways to
revive the stalled Syrian-Israeli peace talks.
</P>
<P>
On Monday in Damascus, al-Assad also held talks with Lebanese
President Elias Hrawi to coordinate their stances on the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Syrian Ambassador in Cairo Isa Darwish was quoted today by the
Cairo press as saying that the meeting between Mubarak and
al-Assad would produce positive and important results.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has expressed
willingness to resume peace talks with Syria.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has reportedly put forward the so-called "Lebanon
First" proposal, under which Israel will pull out its troops from
the Israeli self-styled security zone in south Lebanon in exchange
for Syria's help in disarming the Lebanese pro-Iranian Hezbollah
guerillas and ensuring security on Israel's northern border with
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
But both Lebanon and Syria rejected the proposal. During their
talks Monday, al-Assad and Hrawi agreed to adopt a common stand on
the peace moves with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa said Tuesday that the
Mubarak-al-Assad meeting comes within the framework of constant
Egyptian-Syrian coordination on the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, the first Arab state to make peace with Israel in 1979,
has been playing an active role in pushing forward the Middle East
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak telephoned Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat Tuesday
night to inform him of the ongoing diplomatic efforts to push
forward the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Calls for Greater Market Access in SAARC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Indian Lok Sabha (lower house
of parliament) Speaker P.A. Sangma today urged South Asian
countries to grant greater market access to each other to
strengthen economic cooperation, the Press Trust of India said
today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a seminar here, Sangma said that the economic
expansion and prosperity are being hindered in South Asian
countries because of their excessive emphasis on the
"self-reliance" philosophy and consequent dependence on the
domestic market.
</P>
<P>
"A country needs to give access to its own market, if is to
gain access to other markets," he said at the seminar on
"Perceptions and Perspectives of India's role in SAARC (South
Asian Association For Regional Cooperation)."
</P>
<P>
Describing market access as a "two-way traffic," he said South
Asian countries with their inward looking approaches have been
losing out over the years to other countries, which have promoted
free interaction and trade with other nations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Oil Group o Continue Investing in Iran, Libya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The French oil group Total said
today that it will go ahead with its program of investment in Iran
and Libya in spite of U.S. threat of economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the English-language newspaper
International Herald Tribune published today, Thierry Desmarets,
president of Total, said that the policies of embargo or economic
isolation will not bring about solution to the problems of
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Desmarets said it is better to develop economic ties with these
countries in order to "increase their political maturity."
</P>
<P>
"What has become extravagant is that the United States is one
against all," he said. "We count on the government of France and
other governments to see to it that European and French enterprises
will not be affected by these laws."
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton signed a congressional bill into
law on Monday, authorizing economic and financial sanctions
against any foreign company or individual who invest more than 40
million U.S. dollars in energy section of Iran and Libya.
</P>
<P>
Desmarets said what worries France and other European countries
most is that nothing seems to be able to prevent the United States
from adopting in future new measures similar to the Helms-Burton
law and d'Amato law.
</P>
<P>
"This is why we are preparing counter-measures to allow European
enterprises to keep their freedom," he said.
</P>
<P>
Total signed in 1995 a contract worth 600 million U.S. dollars
with Iran to develop two offshore oil fields in Sirri in the Gulf,
after the U.S. government ordered the U.S. oil company Conoco to
withdraw from there.
</P>
<P>
Total is now looking for partners in the project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
