<HEADLINE> Nuclear-Free Zone Expected in Southeast Asia This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Association of Southeast
Asian Nations (ASEAN) expected to implement its treaty to
establish a Southeast Asian Nuclear-Weapon-Free Zone (SEANWFZ)
some time later this year, according to Indonesian Foreign
Minister Ali Alatas.
</P>
<P>
"We are now working to ensure the early implementation of our
treaty on SEANWFZ. We hope that this can take place before ASEAN
leaders meet in Jakarta for their first informal summit later this
year," said Alatas here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The SEANWFZ was a significant step towards the realization of a
zone of peace, freedom and neutrality in Southeast Asia, Alatas
said at the seminar on "ASEAN Strategies and Actions" organized
jointly by the Indonesian forum and Indonesian executive circle.
</P>
<P>
"It also constitutes another major contribution from ASEAN to
global peace and stability," the minister added.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN leaders from Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam signed the treaty at
their Bangkok Summit in december 1995, which also linked Laos,
Cambodia and Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
According to Alatas, ASEAN would continue to build and
strengthen links with Europe through the Asia-Europe Meeting and
with the American continent through the Asia-Pacific Economic
Cooperation forum. 
