<HEADLINE> Nigeria Declares Uninformed of Cameroun's Fresh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government said
Tuesday it is yet to be officially briefed on Cameroun's latest
territorial claim to the Lake Chad area in northeast Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The new development, which arises from the protracted dispute
over the oil-rich Bakassi Peninsula, is "a policy development
which only the government can handle," Nigerian Director of Defence
Information Brig.-gen. Fred Chijuka said.
</P>
<P>
Comeroun has asked the world court to "specify definitively"
the frontier between it and Nigeria from Lake Chad in the north
to the sea in the south.
</P>
<P>
Chijuka said: "If they (Cameroun) are making claim to the
area, it is government that will reply the world court where they
made the claim. They will then tell the military what to do."
</P>
<P>
Although it is yet to be officially briefed on the
development, the Nigerian government will take care of it, the
defence spokesman said, adding that "ouo duty is to protect the
nation's interest".
</P>
<P>
"We are in Bakassi peninsula today because government said
we should assert our presence. whatever their claim may be, it is
nothing to worry about. It is not anything to give the military
sleepless nights," Chijuka declared. 
</P>
