<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Radish Sprouts Probed as Cause of Japan's Food Poison </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Health Minister Naoto Kan
said today that radish sprouts in school lunches were probably the
cause of series of food poisoning incidents that has sickened
6,309 school children in the country.
</P>
<P>
The radish sprouts became suspect of ill-making food after an
investigation eliminated most other potential infection sources on
the menus in different school districts served on days the deadly
E. coli O-157 bacteria apparently broke out, Kan told the Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Kan said traces of the bacteria were not found in samples of
sprouts at the grower that provided them to the schools, but the
possibility of infection of the bacteria cannot be ruled out by
way of epidemiological studies.
</P>
<P>
The outbreak of E. coli O-157 bacteria, whose symptoms include
stomach pains, bloody diarrhea and kidney failure, has hit Japan
nationwide, killing seven people and sickening more than 9,000.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese Authorities had suspected that school lunches were
the cause of the outbreak in Sakai, 480 kilometers (300 miles)
west of Tokyo, the hardest hit city. But they had not been able
to pinpoint the specific food after hundreds of tests on food
samples. 
</P>
</TEXT>
