<HEADLINE> Japan's Overseas Banks Ordered to Improve Management </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Japan's central bank has ordered
the U.S. branches of the leading Japanese banks to improve their
risk management in an effort to avoid more embarrassing scandals,
said an official from Bank of Japan here today.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of Japan investigated risk-management methods at the
overseas branches from late last year to spring this year, finding
weaknesses in the banks' management of securities as well as in
systems to prevent fraud in electronic transactions, an
unidentified official from the Bank of Japan was quoted as saying
on the Financial Times.
</P>
<P>
The investigation was conducted in response to a major scandal
involving the Daiwa Bank. In the Daiwa affair, a rogue trader at
the bank's New York branch racked up losses of 1.1 billion
U.S. dollars in unauthorized trades. Some critics blamed
inadequate risk-management procedures at Japanese banks.
</P>
<P>
The Daiwa debacle was a major blow to the Japanese banking
system, which has also been hit with massive bad debts from heavy
speculative lending in the late 1980s and early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Daiwa was forced to close its U.S. operations and paid 340
million dollars in fines after pleading guilty in February for
hiding the losses at its New York branch. 
</P>
</TEXT>
