<HEADLINE> Assad Arrives in Egypt for Talks with Mubarak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Syrian President Hafez al-Assad
arrived in the Egyptian Mediterranean port city of Alexandria
today for talks with his Egyptian counterpart Hosni Mubarak on the
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was expected to mainly deal with the Syrian and
Lebanese tracks of the peace process and Israel's decision to
restart construction of Jewish settlements in the Palestinian
territories of the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
The Arabs, particularly the Palestinians, have criticized
Israel's decision on settlements as an obstacle to peace and a
violation of agreements already reached between Israel and the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Today's meeting comes just four days after Assad met with
Jordan's King Hussein in Damascus Saturday to explore ways to
revive the stalled Syrian-Israeli peace talks.
</P>
<P>
On Monday in Damascus, Assad also held talks with Lebanese
President Elias Hrawi to coordinate their stances on the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Syrian Ambassador in Cairo Isa Darwish was quoted today by the
Cairo press as saying that the meeting between Mubarak and Assad
would produce positive and important results.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has expressed
willingness to resume peace talks with Syria.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has reportedly put forward the so-called "Lebanese
first" proposal, under which Israel will pull out its troops from
an enclave in south Lebanon in exchange for Syria's help in
disarming Lebanese pro-Iranian Hezbollah guerillas and ensuring
security on Israel's northern border with Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
But both Lebanon and Syria rejected the proposal. During their
talks Monday, Assad and Hrawi agreed to adopt a common stand on
the peace moves with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa said Tuesday that the
Mubarak-Assad meeting comes within the framework of constant
Egyptian-Syrian coordination on the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, the first Arab state to make peace with Israel in 1979,
has been playing an active role in pushing forward the Mideast
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak telephoned Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat Tuesday
night to inform him of the ongoing diplomatic efforts to push
forward the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
