<HEADLINE> Manila Confident of Achieving Tax Revenue Target </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
said here today that by 1998 his country would be able to attain
the tax revenue target of 18 percent of the Gross National Product
(GNP).
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a meeting of the Legislative-Executive Development
Advisory Council, Ramos said that the country's tax revenues have
moved up to 16.3 percent of the GNP at present from 14.7 percent
when he assumed office in 1992.
</P>
<P>
"We are trying to reach 18 percent in 1998 which is actually
the average in ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian Nations)
countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We would really like to catch up with the highest performer in
tax effort like Malaysia and Singapore at 21 percent," he said,
adding that the enactment of measures under the comprehensive tax
reform program will greatly boost efforts to improve tax
collection.
</P>
<P>
The expeditious passage of the tax reform program would also
mean more money to support much-needed, much-delayed projects and
programs for the Filipino people, he said.
</P>
<P>
The government is expecting some 13.6 billion pesos (519
million U.S. dollars) of tax revenues this year from the tax
reform program, which is still awaiting the approval of the
congress.  
</P>
