<HEADLINE> Continued Talks Expected Between Nigeria, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has invited the
Commonwealth Ministerial Action Group (CMAG) to a meeting slated
for August 29 and 30 in Abuja to continue the dialogue the two
sides had in London last June.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to CMAG Chairman Stan Mudenge, which was made
known Tuesday, Nigerian Foreign Minister Tom Ikimi said his
country expects the CMAG delegation to comprise its entire
eight-nation membership and Secretary General of the Commonwealth
Emeka Anyaoku, who is Nigerian.
</P>
<P>
The minister termed the London meeting "a positive step in the
establishment of dialogue" between the two sides. It afforded an
opportunity for Nigeria to "express its concern over the unfair
suspension from the commonwealth".
</P>
<P>
The London meeting reportedly ended in a stalement, in which
Nigeria's hope for re-admission to the organization was dashed.
</P>
<P>
The invitation to CMAG is viewed as step by the Nigerian
government to soft-pedal its face-off with the Commonwealth.
</P>
<P>
The government up to late June this year insisted that CMAG
stay out of the country until the Commonwealth reconsiders the
suspension of Nigeria from the 53-member body.
</P>
<P>
Nnigeria was suspended from the Commonwealth last November
following its execution of nine Ogoni minority activists. The
Commonwealth summit later set up CMAG to monitor compliance with
the principles of the Harare declaration on human rights in all
African member states. 
</P>
