<HEADLINE> Japan to Extend Large Loan to Saudi Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese Export-Import
Bank will extend a 600 million Saudi riyals (160 million U.S.
dollars) loan to Saudi Arabia under an agreement newly signed with
Saudi Methanol Company to reinforce the facilities of the company.
</P>
<P>
This is the first direct investment loan that the Export-Import
Bank of Japan has ever made to the kingdom, according to Tuesday's
Saudi Arabian English language daily Arab News which arrived here
today.
</P>
<P>
The loan will be used to reinforce the facilities at which the
company produces methanol from natural gas supplied by Saudi
Aramco, the largest Saudi state-owned company dealing with oil,
through the technology provided by Mitsubishi Gas Chemical
Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi Methanol Company is a 50-50 joint venture between
Saudi Arabia and Japan with a consortium of Japanese companies
led by Mitsubishi Gas Chemical Company.
</P>
<P>
This will be the second expansion of the operations of the
company, which currently produces 1.27 million metric tons of
methanol per year.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Japanese Ambassador to Saudi Arabia Minoru
Tamba as saying that "this significant move will make the company
the largest producer of methanol in the world." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> June Sees the Biggest Fall in UK Industrial Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
According to figures released Tuesday by the Office for
National Statistics (ONS), total industrial production, which
includes factory output, oil and gas extraction and energy
production, fell by 1.1 percent in June, compared with a rise of
0.8 percent in May.
</P>
<P>
It was the biggest monthly drop since November 1992.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturing output in June fell 0.3 percent, and 0.5 percent
year-on-year, the lowest level since June 1993. The sector has
failed to grow for three successive quarters.
</P>
<P>
The ONS estimated for the seventh successive month that output
would remain flat in both total industrial production and
manufacturing industries, with energy production depressed by the
warm weather and activity in the North Sea constrained by
maintenance work.
</P>
<P>
Economists believe that with political pressures weighing
heavily on the Chancellor of the Exchequer Kenneth Clarke's mind,
the latest figures may offer him useful ammunition to argue for
another interest rate cut in the autumn. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
