<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 09:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Opposes Tougher UN Sanctions on Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Egypt has reiterated that it is
opposed to imposing tougher sanctions on Sudan for the country's
failure to hand over three suspects involved in an assassination
attempt on Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak last year.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt has refused from the very beginning the toughening of
sanctions against Sudan," Adel el-Safty, first secretary at the
Foreign Ministry, was quoted today as saying by a local
English-language newspaper.
</P>
<P>
But he warned Khartoum Tuesday that Egypt could not keep up
this stance for long, according to The Egyptian Gazette.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt alone opposed the general and growing trend in the
Security Council to increase sanctions but it will not be able to
keep this stand forever," he said. "We urge Sudan to implement the
Security Council's resolutions so sanctions are not increased."
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Security Council sources said Egypt was spearheading
a move to impose an air embargo against Sudan, adding to the
diplomatic and travel ban slapped by the council earlier this year
for Khartoum's failure to extradite the three men accused of
trying to kill Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
The council sources said Egypt was still opposed to economic
sanctions against Sudan for the adverse effect they would have on
the Sudanese people.
</P>
<P>
Egypt had also rejected military sanctions because they would
hamper the Sudanese government's 13-year-old battle against rebels
in the south, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt is concerned with the welfare of the Sudanese people and
wants to keep up good neighborly relations. We hope for a
reciprocal feeling from Sudan," Safty was quoted by the paper as
saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
