<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 08:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan to Raise Work-Permit Fees for Foreign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Jordan will raise fees for work
permits for guest workers in the kingdom from 300 dinars (about
520 U.S. dollars) to 1,200 dinars (about 1,680 dollars) to further
stem the flow of foreign labor.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Labor Abdul Hafez Shakhanbeh said the government
"is determined to halt the flow of foreign labor to create
employment opportunities for Jordanian workers," according to
today's English-language daily Jordan Times.
</P>
<P>
The number of foreign residents have increased from 250,000 in
1995 to approximately 300,000 this year, of whom nearly 30,000
are unemployed but continue to reside in the country.
</P>
<P>
Shakhanbeh said the fees for work permits will be raised by
10-25 percent for Arab laborers in agriculture, 100-150 percent
for Arab laborers in other fields, and 300-400 percent for foreign
laborers.
</P>
<P>
In order to ensure access to information about foreigners in
the country, the Jordanian government has requested employers and
landlords to inform the local police station about the foreigners
residing with or working for them within 48 hours of the
foreigners' arrival in the country.
</P>
<P>
"Violators of the new regulations would pay 50-100 dinars
(70-140 dollars) fine per day," the minister warned.
</P>
<P>
He said his ministry would cooperate with the Ministry of
Interior through the issuance of instructions to border police
posts to enforce the new regulations.
</P>
<P>
Visitors will have their passports stamped upon entry with a
stipulation that they are banned from taking up employment in the
country and they should inform the border police officers of their
residence address during their stay.
</P>
<P>
"Violators will be expelled from the country and will be denied
re-entry," the labor minister said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Jordanian authorities accused foreign labor of
aggravating the high unemployment in the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
"Guest workers have noticeably increased in numbers, adversely
affecting the Jordanian labor market and aggravating the
unemployment situation in Jordan," said the minister a few days
ago.
</P>
<P>
The unemployment rate in the kingdom stands at 15 percent
according to official figures, but analysts here believe that the
actual number would be more than 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, those foreign laborers without work permission, who
were classified by the Jordanian government as "illegal workers,"
were mainly from Egypt and Syria and employed in the trades which
were despised by Jordanians for its "long work hour and low pay."
</P>
<P>
The government tried hard, but in vain, to reduce the number
of foreign labor in the kingdom last year.
</P>
<P>
The authorities demanded last year that foreign workers in the
kingdom get their work permission from departments concerned or
leave the country within three months.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe that the new moves to curb the inflow
of foreign labors into the kingdom were aimed at easing the burden
of unemployment regarding the current conflict between the
government and the opposition parties over lifting the subsidies
on bread which the latter accused of lowering the standard of
living. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 08:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Oil Industry Dismisses US Sanction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Iranian oil industry sources said
today the latest sanctions imposed by the United States on Iran
will have neither short-term or long-term impact on the country's
oil and gas sector.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian National Oil Company (NIOC) stated in a report
today that it became very clear that Iran would face no problem
now or in the future since Europe angrily reacted against the
United States.
</P>
<P>
The oil industry is the pillar of Iran's economy. Iran earns
about 14-16 billion U.S. dollars by exporting crude oil and the
oil export revenue accounts for about 70 percent of the total
export income of the country.
</P>
<P>
The company report noted "it was the U.S. companies and not
Iran that suffered from the June 1995 sanction and it is going to
be even worse this time."
</P>
<P>
The company was referring to a 600-million-dollar contract for
offshore exploration at Sirri oilfields. Originally the American
company Conoco had the contract to undertake the project but
abandoned it because of a ban imposed by President Bill Clinton in
June 1995.
</P>
<P>
An NIOC official said, "This time the American political
prestige is at stake and it will surely be damaged as the
U.S. administration will not be able to receive from its European
allies what it expects."
</P>
<P>
Iran's Oil Minister Gholamreza Aqazadeh said recently,
"U.S. sanctions against Iran have resulted in a loss of more than
2 billion dollars on American oil companies."
</P>
<P>
Aqazadeh claimed, "Having 92 billion barrels of crude oil
reserves, the Islamic Republic of Iran is one of the significant
players in the world energy arena."
</P>
<P>
To thwart American sanction, the Iranian oil industry has
announced a total of 11 oil and gas key projects worth at least 7
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Iran had said that more than 120 foreign oil and gas companies
offered their bids in the Iranian oil and gas sector. The French
company Total reportedly rushed to fill the vacuum left by the
American firm.
</P>
<P>
Iran is the second largest oil exporter in the world. It pumps
3.6 million barrels of oil and exports 2.5 million barrels every
day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President Meets Noted Geologists From Around World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIDAIHE, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
today congratulated the convening of the ongoing 30th
International Geological Congress in China, and said he hoped that
the Congress will encourage the development of geological science
in the 21st century, continuing the achievements in the field made
in this century.
</P>
<P>
Jiang made the remarks at a meeting with a group of noted
geologists from around the world who are attending the 10-day
Congress, which opened Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Extending a sincere welcome to the participants, Jiang said
this is the first time that the Congress has been convened in
China, and the third time in an Asian country since the first
meeting in 1878. He said he believed that the Congress will
promote the development of geological science through extensive
academic exchange.
</P>
<P>
The fundamental task of the geological sciences lies in
understanding the earth, and using that understanding to guarantee
the natural resources required for human existence, and also to
protect the environment, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
To make this happen, Jiang added, geological science has a
heavy and historical responsibility, and must develop into an
outstanding scientific branch. Therefore, the mission of
geologists is both difficult and glorious, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that all countries and regions have their own
respective advantages in terms of natural resources. It has become
an historical trend for all countries to conduct international
exchanges and cooperation, and to supplement each other with their
benefits.
</P>
<P>
He said he hoped that the geologists attending the Congress
will strengthen cooperative studies in order to advance global
geological science.
</P>
<P>
William S. Fyfe, president of the International Union of
Geological Sciences, Tatashi Sato, president of the 29th
International Geological Congress, and Robin Brett, chairman of
the Academic Planning of the 28th International Geological
Congress, spoke at the meeting, thanking China for its efforts as
host of the Congress.
</P>
<P>
Fyfe defined the ongoing 30th Congress as the largest
geological congress in history, which is expected to bring the
geological sciences into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The ongoing Congress focuses on looking toward the future and
settling major issues facing mankind and nature, Fyfe said, adding
that the event will provide a good opportunity for the development
of the geological sciences and even mankind.
</P>
<P>
He said he believes that geologists from all countries will
make greater contributions to society after this Congress.
</P>
<P>
Also present at the meeting were Song Ruixiang, President of
the Organizing Committee of the Congress and minister of Geology
and Mineral Resources, and Liu Huaqiu, director of the Foreign
Affairs Office of the State Council.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Congress Party Caps Phone Tapping Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The Indian National Congress
(Congress party) Tuesday withdrew its allegation that the
government was tapping the telephone lines of senior party leaders
and reiterated its commitment to the government of H.D. Deve
Gowda, the Financial Express said today.
</P>
<P>
The recent controversy on the phone tapping issue had posed a
threat to the relations between the ruling United Front and the
Congress party which is supporting the government from the
outside.
</P>
<P>
"There is no question of blackmailing the government. We will
continue to support it for five years," a Congress party spokesman
said in response to speculations that the tapping controversy was
a Congress party strategy to browbeat the government.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the party took up the matter with Prime
Minister Deve Gowda soon after reports appeared in the press that
the telephones of several leaders of the Congress party, including
that of Congress President P.V. Narasimha Rao, were being tapped.
</P>
<P>
There were also reports that Rao's house was under surveillance
by plainclothesmen.
</P>
<P>
"The prime minister assured us that there is no tapping
underway. We were satisfied. Now he has ordered a CBI (Central
Bureau of Investigation) inquiry and, therefore, the chapter is
closed," the spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
