<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Nazi Officer Refuses to Face Trial in Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Former Nazi officer Erich Priebke on
Tuesday said he refused to be extradited to Germany and face
trials there on charges of war crimes for his involvement in a
1944 massacre in Italy, officials said here.
</P>
<P>
President of the Italian Court of Appeal Tommaso Figliuzzi
talked with Priebke for two hours in a Roman prison where he was
being held.
</P>
<P>
His defense lawyer Velio Di Rezze said Priebke told Figliuzzi
that he doesn't want to be extradited to Germany.
</P>
<P>
The lawyer said Priebke had said he wanted to return to
Argentina, where he had been hiding for almost half a century, but
the request was turned down by Argentine President Carlos Menem on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Attempts to extradite the former Nazi officer arose when he
was freed last Thursday by an Italian court.
</P>
<P>
The Rome Military Court ruled that a statute of limitation
meant Priebke could not be punished and declared him a free man
despite being found guilty of the massacre of 335 civilians.
</P>
<P>
Priebke, now 83, took part in the massacre on March 24, 1944,
at the Ardeatine Caves near Rome. He fled to Argentina after the
end of World War II but was extradited to Italy in November, 1995,
to face a trial which began on May 8.
</P>
<P>
The verdict sparked an explosion of anger and protests in and
outside of Italy immediately.
</P>
<P>
Italy's Minister for Justice, Giovanni Maria Flick, delivered a
request to maintain Priebke's incarceration -- a legal formality
that must be completed within 10 days when people are being held
pending an extradition request.
</P>
<P>
Germany requested to extradite Priebke as well as another
former SS officer, Major Karl Hass, who was a key witness in the
war crimes trial of Priebke, after the Roman court issued the
verdict.
</P>
<P>
Hass, now 84, admitted taking part in the massacre but was
granted immunity in the Italian trial in exchange for his
testimony. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
