<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Industry Dragged Down Last Month By Flood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Production at China's industries
slowed slightly in July, due to high temperatures and severe
floods in the southern parts of the country, the State Statistics
Bureau said today.
</P>
<P>
The bureau said in a report that the Chinese industry turned
out 152.4 billion yuan-worth of products last month, a real growth
of 12.2 percent on an annual basis, while the sector showed a
13-14 percent growth rate every month during the past half year.
</P>
<P>
From January to July, the country's industry completed a total
of 1,058.5 billion yuan-worth of products, up 13.1 percent on a
year-to-year basis.
</P>
<P>
The state sector grew the slowest in July at 4.6 percent, while
collectively-owned industrial enterprises grew 17.2 percent on a
yearly basis. Industrial enterprises with other forms of ownership
grew 12.6 percent. All registered drops in their development.
</P>
<P>
Heavy industry suffered more from the prolonged hot weather and
flooding than the light industries, the report said.
</P>
<P>
"The heavy industry completed an output value of 90.8 billion
yuan in July, 10.9 percent more than in the same month last year,"
according to the report. "The growth rate is 2.2 percentage points
down from the last year."
</P>
<P>
The report showed that light industry maintained its growth
momentum of the first half of the year, turning out 61.6 billion
yuan-worth of products last month. It grew 13.9 percent on a
yearly basis.
</P>
<P>
China's economic efficiency improved slightly during the second
quarter, according to the report. During the January-June period,
the state-owned industrial enterprises reaped a net profit of 3.5
billion yuan after losses were deducted from profits.
</P>
<P>
However, high loss volume, huge debts owed by the companies and
stockpiles of goods are still the major ailments of the state
sector.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
