<HEADLINE> Ewenki Writer in Inner Mongolia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HUHHOT, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Oerdu, the first writer from the
Ewenki ethnic group in north China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous
Region, is known for his novels about the lives of hunters.
</P>
<P>
Many of his works, such as "The Request of a Hunter," "The
Elder and the Child," and "The Forest Story," have received
recognition and prizes in the past 15 years.
</P>
<P>
In 1986 and 1993, Oerdu visited the United States, where he
gave lectures about his writing and the Ewenki people.
</P>
<P>
Oerdu began hunting when he was a middle school student. His
experiences in the forest strengthened his character and his deep
affection for the Ewenki people.
</P>
<P>
He said that he wanted to show the world about the lives of the
Ewenki ethnic group, and stress the importance of maintaining a
balanced environment and protecting nature.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the Chinese edition, his works have been
translated into English, French, German and Japanese. 
