<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Africa, Zimbabwe Settle Trade Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 7 (Xinhua) -- South Africa and Zimbabwe
have finally settled a lengthy trade dispute, which caused the
tense economic relations between the two countries, a local daily
"the Citizen" reported today.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued on Tuesday in Johannesburg, the
Department of Trade and Industry said agreement was reached in
principle at a meeting late last week for South Africa to lower
trade tariffs on textile imports from Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, signed by South African Trade and Industry
Minister Alec Erwin and Zimbabwean Industry and Commerce Minister
Nathan Shamuyarira, came after four years of negotiations between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"The meeting was held in a positive and cordial atmosphere and
marks a new phase in trade relations between the two countries,"
said the statement.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, South Africa's Deputy Director-general for Foreign
Trade Relations, Busi Gaboo, declared the forming of a joint
working group for trade investigateions.
</P>
<P>
"We only reached agreement on textiles and clothing, and the
duties will change from September 1," said Gaboo.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, tariffs on textiles and clothing, which
make up a major part of zimbabwean exports, would be cut to about
30 percent.
</P>
<P>
The agreement with Zimbabwe would also form the basis on which
other trade deals with Southern African Development Community
(SADC) members would be negotiated, Gaboo added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dalai Lama's Attack on Population Transfer into Tibet Refuted (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, AUGUST 7 (Xinhua) -- An anthropology professor today
debunked as "sheer fabrication" the assertion made by Dalai Lama
in Britain's Parliament recently that the Chinese government has
"moved large numbers of people into Tibet," causing Tibetans to
become an insignificant minority ethnic group in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Ma Rong, director of the Sociology and Anthropology
Institute of Beijing University, said that in truth, Tibetans
account for 95.5 percent of the total population of China's Tibet
Autonomous Region, and Han people just three percent.
</P>
<P>
"Han people really constitute a minority ethnic group in
Tibet," he said. "As a scholar, I believe irrefutable facts and
reliable data only."
</P>
<P>
Ma received a master's degree and Ph.D. from Brown University
in the United States in the 1980s. Later, he studied as a
post-doctoral student in the John King Fairbank Center of Harvard
University, also in the US.
</P>
<P>
According to Ma, the central and local governments in China
began in the late 1970s and early 1980s to tighten control over
the transfer of people into Tibetan-inhabited areas. As a result,
the number of Han people moving into such areas has decreased.
</P>
<P>
Since China initiated the policy of the reform and opening up
in 1979, farmers in less developed areas in central and western
China have been moving to coastal areas to seek jobs, he
noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dalai Lama's Attack on Population Transfer into Tibet Refuted (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In Tibet, Han people are mostly construction workers for
projects undertaken by other areas in China, he said, adding that
they are working there on a rotating basis.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that since the 1950s, some 200,000 people from
other parts of China have worked in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Ma said that the people are university graduates, young
government officials, doctors, teachers, engineers and
technicians. After working in Tibet for several years, they will
return to their hometowns to reunite with their families.
</P>
<P>
The Dalai Lama's claim that the Tibet ethnic group has a
population of six million is "totally groundless," Ma said.
</P>
<P>
The assertion by some Western media organizations that the
Tibetan population has "dropped dramatically" and that "800,000
Tibetans were starved to death" is also totally groundless and not
substantiated by specific statistical figures, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
A new survey conducted by his colleagues under his guidance
demonstrates that the population of Tibetans in Tibet nearly
doubled in 42 years, from 1.15 million in 1952 to 2.23 million in
1994, rising at an average annual rate of 1.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The survey also indicates that during that period, the
population of Tibetans in other areas that exercise regional
autonomy grew even faster than that of Tibetans in Tibet, rising
at an annual rate of 2.14 to 2.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The national population census in 1990 shows that the Tibetan
population was 4.59 million, ranking ninth among the 55 minority
ethnic groups in China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dalai Lama's Attack on Population Transfer into Tibet Refuted (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
According to a report accompanying the survey, the rapid growth
of the Tibetan population is largely due to increased
appropriations by the central government to Tibet, that have been
offered since democratic reform was carried out there in 1959.
</P>
<P>
All social undertakings in Tibet, especially medical care, have
been growing rapidly since then, resulting in the decrease in the
Tibetans' mortality rate and a substantial rise in the birth rate.
</P>
<P>
Before 1959, the serf system inhibited the growth of the
Tibetan population; for several centuries, harsh living conditions
and unsophisticated medical services caused a decline in the
Tibetan population.
</P>
<P>
The report said that family planning was first practiced among
the Han people in 1975. Yet Tibetan workers did not take birth
control measures until 1982, and then on a small scale.
</P>
<P>
In fact, Tibetans in agricultural and pastoral areas are not
subject to any compulsory family planning measures.
</P>
<P>
According to Prof. Ma, the Dalai Lama has asserted that Tibet
actually includes other lands in a greater Tibetan region, which
covers the Tibet Autonomous Region and Tibetan-inhabited areas in
Gansu, Qinghai, Sichuan and Yunnan provinces.
</P>
<P>
Ma said that this claim is neither true to historical facts nor
realistic, because the local government never administered a
greater Tibetan region, and that when Tibet was liberated by
peaceful means, the local government administered only the
present-day Tibetan Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Scholars on Tibetology agree that the survey uses irrefutable
facts and reliable data to dismiss the attack on the Chinese
government by the Dalai Lama, together with a small number of
people in the West, by taking advantage of the disagreement over
the actual Tibetan population.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
