<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HIV/AIDS Cases Increase to 420 in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Thirteen more HIV/AIDS cases have
been detected in Indonesia, bringing the official number of the
cases to 420 in the country, reports said here today.
</P>
<P>
The new cases were detected in blood samples over a one-month
period, Hadi Marjanto, an official of the Health Ministry, said in
Bali, about 1,000 kilometers east of Jakarta, on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
All the 13 cases with the human immune-deficiency virus (HIV)
or the acquired immune-deficiency syndrome (AIDS) are
heterosexual, he said.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-three people have died of AIDS in Indonesia, according to
Health Minister Sujudi.
</P>
<P>
He said the actual number of people with HIV or AIDS in the
country could be "100 times higher than reported" because only a
small number of people have had their blood tested.
</P>
<P>
Sujudi warned that if AIDS is not properly controlled in
Indonesia, up to 2.5 million people could be infected by the year
2000, which breaks down to an estimated 150 people contracting it
every day.
</P>
<P>
"When Indonesia has 2.5 million people with HIV/AIDS, the
country will have to spend over 13 billion U.S. dollars a year to
get the epidemic under control," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
