<HEADLINE> Nepali House Looks into Dispute over Sugar Import </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 7 (Xinhua) -- A Nepali house panel is
investigating a dispute between two ministries over 40,000 metric
tons of sugar import from India, local newspapers reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Public Accounts Committee under the lower house today
summoned senior officials of the Foreign Ministry and the Supplies
Ministry to attend its meeting on the controversial import deal of
Indian sugar.
</P>
<P>
The dispute arose at a cabinet meeting last week when Supplies
Minister Gajendra Narayan Singh accused the Foreign Ministry of
interfering in his ministry's work on the import deal.
</P>
<P>
The Nepali cabinet meeting had reportedly decided to import the
batch of Indian sugar through the state-run National Trading
Corporation or Salt Trading Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The reports said the Supplies Ministry had written a letter to
India's State Trading Corporation last month, asking it to make
the sugar deal with a Nepali private company -- Pearl Trading
Concern.
</P>
<P>
But officials of the Foreign Ministry said they had informed
the Indian side to supply the sugar to Nepal's state corporations
after receiving a letter on the issue from the Indian embassy here
in mid-July.
</P>
<P>
The Indian government customarily provides certain quantities
of sugar to Nepal every year.
</P>
<P>
Secretaries of the two ministries are expected to make their
statements over the dispute at a hearing of the house panel today.
</P>
<P>
Sugar and fertilizer imports have often been sensitive issues
in Nepal, with corruption charges against officials and
businessmen involved in these deals.  
</P>
</TEXT>
