<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White Farmers Vow to Stay in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's white commercial
farmers, uneasy with the government's land redistribution
programme, said on Tuesday they would not leave the country and
pledged to help the country's majority black farmers.
</P>
<P>
Commercial Farmers Union (CFU) President Peter Mcsporran said
his predominantly white union members accepted the need for more
equitable distribution of land.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the 53rd CFU congress, Mcsporran said farmers
could only increase productivity if they had security of tenure.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the ruling ZANU PF government and the CFU, whose
4,500 members own about 70 percent of Zimbabwe's arable land, soured
in 1992 when the land acquisition act was introduced.
</P>
<P>
Under the act, the state is enpowered to compulsorily acquire
land, mainly from white commercial farmers, for resettlement of
the largely landless blacks.
</P>
<P>
The land acquisition exercise was perceived as "racism in
reverse" and the commercial farmers turned to the international
community for support.
</P>
<P>
The government, riled by the invitation of outsiders, told the
farmers to leave the country if they wished, reiterating it would
not abandon the resettlement programme until the people presently
crowded on parched land were moved to better areas.
</P>
<P>
"We are not planning to leave, we are not expatriates nor are
we all white," said Mcsporran. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
