<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China Province Intensifies Water, Soil Conservation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The densely-populated east China
province of Zhejiang, which has more mountains and less farmland,
has developed effective measures to prevent soil erosion.
</P>
<P>
New regulations by the provincial government stipulate that
farming is forbidden on any mountainous area that has a slope
above 25 degrees, or in places with a slope of over 20 degrees
that directly face reservoirs.
</P>
<P>
Afforestation and tree-planting will soon resume in these hilly
areas where farming previously has been conducted.
</P>
<P>
According to the new rules, future resource development and
project construction must be carried out simultaneously with water
and soil conservation.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang's mountains and hills make up 70 percent of its total
area of 100,000 sq km. Per capita arable land stands at only 0.03
hectares, or 47 percent of the national average or 16 percent of
the world's average.
</P>
<P>
The local ecological environment has been seriously damaged in
recent years due to natural disasters, and also the deterioration
of land caused by farming, lumbering and mining.
</P>
<P>
Remote-sensing census by the Ministry of Water Resources shows
that soil-eroded area in Zhejiang has exceeded 20,000 sq km,
one-fourth of the province's total area. The annual amount of soil
washed away stands at 50 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Serious soil erosion has weakened the fertility of more than
800,000 mu (48,000 hectares) of farmland, and also led to the rise
of the river beds of eight major river systems in the province. A
group of harbors and river courses cannot let ships pass due to
increasing layers of mud.
</P>
<P>
To curb soil erosion, the Zhejiang provincial government
launched a tree-planting campaign in 1989. By 1994, the province
had planted trees on more than 12 million mu (720,000 hectares) of
mountainous areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhejiang Makes Headway in Transportation Facilities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, August 7 (Xinhua) -- A modern transportation network,
including highways, railways, air and sea routes, is making life
easier for travelers in east China's Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang, bordered by the East China Sea, has maintained rapid
economic growth rates over the past few years, but unsophisticated
transportation facilities have severely limited the circulation of
goods.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the provincial government is working to develop
infrastructure facilities by attracting heavy investment from
China and abroad.
</P>
<P>
New highways totaling 4,000 kilometers have been built in the
province over the past five years, bringing the total length of
highway in the province to 34,000 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
More than 95 percent of the villages and townships in the
province have access to highways, a rate higher than the country's
average.
</P>
<P>
The Hangzhou-Shangyu expressway, the first of its kind in
Zhejiang, is an example of the province's determination to boost
highway construction.
</P>
<P>
Since 1991, the province has opened to traffic three trunk
railway lines, which have effectively eased the overloaded railway
system.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the Hangzhou Railway Administration said that
efforts will be made to increase the speed of many passenger
trains, as well.
</P>
<P>
Newly-built airports in Ningbo, Wenzhou, Yiwu and Quzhou have
increased the number of air transport facilities to six, bringing
its air routes to more than 100.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang now has 58 harbors with more than 600 berths, and
navigation courses that link the province with 300 harbors
throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
The 200,000-ton Beilun Harbor is the largest mineral shipping
base in the country, and the 200,000-ton oil harbor in Zhoushan
makes Zhejiang the first province in the country that can berth
super oil tankers, officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
