<HEADLINE> Japan Becomes Second-Largest Investor in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Japan has replaced the United
States to become this year's second largest investor in Shanghai,
China's economic powerhouse, next to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
From January-July, Japan poured nearly 1.2 billion US dollars
into Shanghai, a 38 percent rise over the same period in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has invested more than 19 billion US dollars in
Shanghai, and has more than 6,300 projects in China's largest city.
</P>
<P>
During the seven-month period, Hong Kong's investment in
Shanghai rose 30 percent over the same period in 1995, surpassing
2.5 billion US dollars, and accounting for nearly 40 percent of
total overseas investment in the city during that time.
</P>
<P>
Countries that invested more than 100 million US dollars into
the city during the period include the US, Singapore, the Republic
of Korea and the UK.
</P>
<P>
During the seven months, the city gave the go-ahead to nearly
1,200 overseas-funded projects, attracting overseas investment
from 37 countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
Total contractual investment of the overseas-funded enterprises
this year goes up eight percent, from nearly 5.9 billion US dollars
in the same period in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Average investment for each project this year exceeded 5.3
million US dollars, a big leap from 3.2 million US dollars in 1995.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, nearly 60 percent of overseas-funded projects,
accounting for more than 40 percent of overseas investment, are
involved in industrial production.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investment in Shanghai during the January-July period
of this year is equal to the total in 1992.  
</P>
</TEXT>
