<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Contracted Workers in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The number of contracted and
temporary workers in China has increased by 3.74 million, up 6.1
percent, to hit 64.7 million in the past six months, the State
Statistics Bureau said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
This means that there are 24.56 million more contracted workers
in China, up 61.2 percent over the same 1995 period.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that this indicates the country's employment
structure is moving in a positive direction, and serves as a sign
that the planned economy is shifting to a market economy, as the
number of fixed workers is declining.
</P>
<P>
Contracted workers presently account for 44 percent of the
total number of workers in China, up 16.6 percent from last year.
</P>
<P>
The number of workers in enterprises which have implemented the
contract system accounts for 88.7 percent of the country's total.
</P>
<P>
As for the working format, there are nearly 135 million
long-term workers, a decrease of 720,000 over the same 1995
period, while the number of temporary workers is 11.9 million,
1.04 million more than were reported last year.
</P>
<P>
By May, labor departments in China had investigated 5,270 labor
cases; 4,667 have been settled.
</P>
<P>
So far, more than 100 million workers, including 22.41 million
retired people, are signed up for a nationwide pension plan.
</P>
<P>
In the past, a job as a fixed worker, rather than a contracted or
temporary worker, was regarded as secure employment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
