<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Demand for Phones Likely to Double in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Demand for telephone lines in
India is expected to nearly double in the next six years, the
Indian Express reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to projections made by the Economic Research Unit of
India's Department of Telecom, demand for telephone lines during
the Ninth Five- Year Plan is likely to rise from 18.2 million in
1998 to 31.2 million by the year 2002 compared to the present
level of around 13 to 14 million lines.
</P>
<P>
Demand for cellular phones is also expected to rise to three or
four million by the end of the Ninth Plan period, compared with
the current level of less than 150,000 cellular connections in
four metropolises -- Delhi, Mumbai (Bombay), Calcutta and Madras.
</P>
<P>
Apart from telephones and cellulars, the Economic Research Unit
has projected demand for pagers during the Ninth Plan period to
increase to six million.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
