<HEADLINE> World Bank Urges India to Further Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has warned that
a seven-percent growth rate of Gross Domestic Product (GDP)
witnessed in India in 1995-96 might not be sustained unless urgent
steps are taken to push the reforms process ahead, the Financial
Express said today.
</P>
<P>
In a draft report on the state of the Indian economy, the World
Bank called for initiatives to ensure fiscal discipline,
liberalization of the infrastructure sector, restructuring of
expenditure patterns and better targeting of subsidies.
</P>
<P>
The draft report, worked out by World Bank representatives who
are here on a post-budget fact-finding mission, came up for
discussion between the bank and Indian Finance Ministry officials.
</P>
<P>
The Indian parliament is currently discussing a maiden budget
of the United Front government.  
</P>
