<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Accuses US of Sponsoring State, International </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Ali Akbar
Velayati launched a war of words against the United States,
accusing it of sponsoring state and international terrorism.
</P>
<P>
While addressing Iran-based diplomats here Tuesday, Velayati
said that "the United States is the sponsor and initiator of state
and international terrorism."
</P>
<P>
All Iranian newspapers and dailies today carried Velayati's
statement in front-page as a strong reaction to the latest
sanction bill signed by U.S. President Bill Clinton Monday.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that the relations between the United
States and Iran will be getting more strained and the American
forces will launch an attack against Iran if the United States
finds any evidence of Iran's involvement in any terrorist
attacks against it.
</P>
<P>
Speaking about the tougher American sanctions against Iran, the
Iranian foreign minister said, "Washington did not have the
competence to pass judgements on important international issues."
</P>
<P>
By adopting hostile attitudes and adopting rules which allow
intervention in the internal affairs of other countries by the
U.S. Central Intelligence Agency (CIA), he noted, the United
States has practically interfered in Iran's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
"It is a dangerous sign that the U.S. Congress has been turned
into a center for legitimizing illegal steps. This proves that
the U.S. policies are biased and hegemonic," he added.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the U.S. failure in compelling other countries to
obey its international regulations, he said, "this measure has
been categorically rejected by the international community."
</P>
<P>
He said Washington's adventurous policies were particularly
against those countries with which the White House had serious
differences of view and approach.
</P>
<P>
"The policies will entail dangerous repercussions on future
international relations," he warned.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the baseless and irresponsible charges against
Iran that it supports terrorism and tries to gain access to
weapons of mass destruction, and the threat of using force against
it -- all taking place in violation of international rules and the
United Nations Charter -- were being raised amidst the
presidential election campaign in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Velayati reiterated that Iran condemned terrorism in all its
forms. "We believe that resolving this international dilemma
requires the cooperation of the international community," he added.
</P>
<P>
Iran had made some proposals for the creation of a
comprehensive and non-selective universal mechanism to combat
against terrorism, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
