<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tourism Grows in Half Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 7 (Xinhua) -- More than 24 million overseas
tourists visited China in the first six months of this year, an
increase of 11.8 percent over the January-June period last year.
</P>
<P>
Statistics released by the China National Tourism
Administration show these visitors brought to the country foreign
exchange earnings of 4.61 billion US dollars, a year-on-year
growth of 15.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The figures indicate that 3.12 million foreign tourists visited
China, a rise of 20.5 percent; there were 20.61 million tourists
from Hong Kong and Macao, a jump of 10.8 percent; the number of
Taiwan tourists reached 776,800, a rise of 4.6 percent; and
overseas Chinese numbered 63,200, an increase of 19.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Of the 15 countries that serve as major sources of tourists to
China, all but one -- Australia -- recorded increases in tourist
arrivals, the figures revealed.
</P>
<P>
Japan, which was China's highest-ranked source country in 1995,
sent 704,700 tourists to China in the first six months, a growth
of 31.1 percent; arrivals from the Republic of Korea, which was
the second largest market last year, rose by 34.9 percent to reach
294,100.
</P>
<P>
Visits by tourists from Canada and Russia rose by more than 30
percent and 23.3 percent, respectively; those from the United
States, Malaysia, Singapore, Mongolia, and Britain grew by over 10
percent; and those from the Philippines, Thailand, Germany,
Indonesia, and France climbed within 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
Of all the overseas tourists, those who stayed overnight in the
country accounted for 87.6 percent, while the day-trippers made up
12.4 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
