<HEADLINE> NZ Party Amends Investment Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 7 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand First said today
it will allow foreigners to buy outright local companies of
non-strategic nature if it is elected to govern the country.
</P>
<P>
Party leader Winston Peters told the Wellington Chamber of
Commerce that the party has amended its foreign investment policy
so the 24.9 percent limit placed on overseas investors applied
only to strategic assets.
</P>
<P>
Peters came to prominence early this year for his stance
against foreign immigration, Asian migrants in particular, and
against foreign investment in NZ.
</P>
<P>
But during a visit to London last month, he amended his
position on foreign investment. Today's statement is a
reaffirmation of the amendment.
</P>
<P>
"Those strategic assets include telecommunications, utilities
such as electricity and gas companies, ports, transport companies
of importance like Air New Zealand and so on," he said.
</P>
<P>
Peters announced that his party will release a full list of
assets covered by the 24.9 percent limit close to the election.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand First will stop state asset sales and legislate to
stop land sales to foreigners, he said.  
</P>
