<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Concerned About Low Inflation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The government's success in
reducing inflation to record lows has raised fears that the
economy could be heading for a slowdown, an English-language
investment paper says.
</P>
<P>
Inflation has fallen sharply from an annualized 20 percent in
July 1995 to 2.6 percent in July this year as the government has
kept a tight grip on the money supply through high interest rates,
a squeeze on bank loans and low grain prices.
</P>
<P>
But monthly inflation has been negative since May and falling
consumer prices are now leading to fears that the economy could
stagnate, according to the Vietnam Investment Review.
</P>
<P>
"Too low inflation is something unusual that needs careful
attention or it can adversely affect the country's production,"
the paper quoted Le Xuan Trinh, chief of the government office, as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Although officials have welcomed the fall in inflation for its
stabilizing effect on socio-economic development, the paper says,
some fear the economy will cool down too much.
</P>
<P>
An official from the state bank was quoted as saying that
negative inflation is not a good sign for the economy as it
indicates stagnating production.
</P>
<P>
"The economy is cooling down and there are fears that supply
will exceed demand, causing gluts of some good," the official said.
</P>
<P>
However, Tran Zuan Gia, deputy minister of planning and
investment, said that although some sectors of the economy may be
affected, he did not believe the country's overall production
would suffer.
</P>
<P>
This summer's negative inflation rates are likely to have a
knock-on effect on next year's price index, Tran Xuan Gia said.
Since inflation rates are calculated on a percentage basis, low
prices this year may inflate the percentage price rises in the
index next year, leading to higher inflation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Urban Dwellers Enjoy Better Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Chinese urban residents enjoyed
an improved quality of life during the first half of this year,
the State Statistics Bureau said today.
</P>
<P>
In the first six months of 1996, the average per capita
expenditure of the urban dwellers was 320 yuan (about 38.5 US
dollars) per month, up 2.9 percent in real terms over the same
1995 period, according to a sample survey of 36,000 households
conducted by the bureau.
</P>
<P>
The survey showed that the urban residents spent 159 yuan on
food per capita each month, an increase of 1.6 percent over
Jan.-June of last year; and 48 yuan on clothing, a rise of five
percent.
</P>
<P>
Each of them spent 12 yuan monthly for education expenses, and
6.7 yuan on entertainment, increases of 14.7 and four percent
respectively over the same period in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Construction said it will provide better water,
gas and public transport services for the people in 36 major
cities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
