<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Anti-Iran, Libya Law Condemned Worldwide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 7 (Xinhua) -- More countries worldwide have
joined Europe in the condemnation of the United States for its new
legislation punishing those who maintain economic relations with
Iran and Libya, reports reaching here say.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the 15-member European Union's (EU) collective
rejection, France, Germany, Britain, Russia, Japan and other
countries have protested individually against the law signed by
U.S. President Bill Clinton Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Iran-Libya Sanctions Act, which came after bombing attacks
in Saudi Arabia in June and Atlanta in July, and the explosion of
TWA Flight 800 in July, would panelize non-U.S. companies
investing more than 40 million U.S. dollars annually in the two
countries' energy sector.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government accuses Iran and Libya of sponsoring
terrorism, although investigations of the cases have reached no
conclusions so far.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, French Foreign Ministry spokesman Yves Couriaux
warned that his country would not stand idly by while its
interests are affected.
</P>
<P>
In Bonn, German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel warned of
possible European retaliation, saying, "the U.S. intents and laws
contradict the bases of the World Trade Organization (WTO) ... we
will not accept them."
</P>
<P>
Economics Minister Guenter Rextod said, "the threat of
extra-territorial sanctions against European companies ... is not
the right way to fight the growth of terrorism."
</P>
<P>
The British Foreign Office said in a statement: "We agree that
there should be a common Western policy ... but we cannot accept
U.S. pressure on its allies to impose sanctions under the threat
of mandatory penalties on our companies."
</P>
<P>
EU Commissioner Leon Brittan said in Brussels that the regional
alliance "will act to defend its rights and interests if they are
jeopardized." Iran and Libya together provide a fifth of all
crude oil imports to the 15 EU member countries.
</P>
<P>
In Russia, the Foreign Ministry said, "we need coordinated
practical measures to improve anti-terrorist cooperation ... not
unilateral steps."
</P>
<P>
Japan's Foreign Ministry, describing the legislation as
possibly "inconsistent with WTO rules," said Tuesday that the
U.S. sanctions are "regrettable."
</P>
<P>
In Tehran, the Iranian Foreign Ministry refuted the U.S. law
promoted by Senator Alfonse d'Amato, saying it violates
international trade regulations and is "doomed to failure."
</P>
<P>
"The world community ... is aware of Clinton's intention to
monopolize the world's energy resources and markets and does not
believe his false charges," said the ministry.
</P>
<P>
Libya also condemned the U.S. law as self-defeating and
selfish. "This measure ... reveals America's selfish reasoning,"
the official news agency JANA said.
</P>
<P>
The law "has damaged and will further damage the American
people's interest and those of its allies," it added.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government banned last year private investment in Iran
and Libya, but U.S. companies have since complained that their
foreign competitors have rushed to fill the vacuum left by the
American pullout. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
