<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drought Hits Central Java, Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- A severe drought has hit many
areas in Indonesia's Central Java province, wilting crops in 6,636
hectares of paddy fields, the Antara news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The water level in several major reservoirs in Central Java,
one of Indonesia's largest rice growing areas, has dropped
drastically while the rainy season is still two months away, said
the report.
</P>
<P>
The Badhe reservoir in Boyolali, with a capacity of 2.4 million
cubic meters and capable of irrigating 1,500 hectares of paddy
fields, has dried up and has developed cracks at its bottom, the
report quoted a local official as saying.
</P>
<P>
The report said a severe drought has stricken 35 villages in
Banjarnegara, a mountainous western regency in the country, where
villagers complained about increasing difficulty to obtain
drinking water over the past month.
</P>
<P>
The official said that drinking water is being transported in
trucks to the drought-affected areas by special teams, which have
been set up by Central Java Governor Soewardi to handle the water
crisis.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
