<HEADLINE> ASEAN Official Praises ASEAN's Role in Regional Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Datok Ajit Singh, secretary
general of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN),
praised the grouping's commitment to peace and stability in the
region, which he said helped the member countries keep peace with
one another in the last 29 years.
</P>
<P>
"They (ASEAN members) have developed 'the ASEAN way' which
emphasizes mutual respect for each other's views, quality,
non-interference in each other's internal affairs, the non use of
force or threat to settle disputes, ... and the importance of
reaching consensus in decision-making," Singh said at a seminar on
"ASEAN Strategies and Actions" here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1967, ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Singh said that with the end of the Cold War, attention was now
focused on consolidating the gains already made and in sustaining
peace and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
He said the ASEAN Regional Forum -- which covers all ASEAN
members and observer countries as well as ASEAN's 10 dialogue
partners -- was the foremost vehicle in the Asian region devoted
to the promotion of confidence-building, the development of
preventive diplomacy and the elaboration of approaches to conflict
resolution.  
</P>
</TEXT>
