<HEADLINE> Canada Provides Aid to China's Flood Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Canada has given 110,000
U.S. dollars to provide humanitarian relief aid to victims of the
recent floods in southern China, a government minister said today.
</P>
<P>
Minister for International Cooperation Pierre Pettigrew said,
"Canada wants to assist those severely affected by the
flooding. Our contribution will help pay for emergency food,
drinking water and medical supplies."
</P>
<P>
The aid consists of two grants of 75,000 Canadian dollars
(about 55,000 U.S. dollars) by the Canadian International
Development Agency (CIDA) to Medecins Sans Frontieres (MSF) and
the International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent
Societies (IFRCS).
</P>
<P>
The grant to MSF will help provide medical care over the next
month to flood victims in Guizhou, Anhui and Zhejiang provinces,
and enable the organization to assess continuing emergency needs,
a news release from CIDA said.
</P>
<P>
The grant to IFRCS will help provide safe drinking water,
medical care, food, clothing and quilts to six southern and
eastern provinces over the next three months. 
</P>
