<HEADLINE> Muslim Rebels Leave Island in Southern Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 7 (Xinhua) -- Some 200 rebels of the MORO
National Liberation Front (MNLF) Tuesday pulled out of Limaong
island in Southern Philippines they seized last Thursday, averting
a full-scale military offensive against them, said reports
reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
The rebels had been given an ultimatum on Monday to leave the
island off Zamboanga city by Southern Command Chief of the
Philippine Armed Forces Lieut. Gen. Ruperto Ambil.
</P>
<P>
The first batch of the MNLF fighters reportedly had withdrawn
earlier in the day, and the remaining troops, who held out in at
least three villages in the eastern part of the island, followed
suit a few hours later.
</P>
<P>
The reports said Ambil had agreed to a request by MNLF general
Abdul Sahrin for an extension of the deadline up to midnight.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Executive Secretary Ruben Torres said the
presidential palace would not treat the occupation of Limaong by
the MNLF rebels as a violation of the ceasefire agreement between
the government and the Muslim secessionist group.
</P>
<P>
The government and the MNLF downplayed the incident by claiming
it was a simple case of misunderstanding. The two sides stressed
that the incident had no effect on the upcoming signing of a
formal peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
Torres Monday announced that the formal peace pact was expected
to be signed in the Indonesian capital of Jakarta by the third or
fourth week of the month.  
</P>
