<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IFC Launches Dual Currency Euro Medium Term Notes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The International Finance
Corporation (IFC), part of the World Bank, today announced the
issue of a 10 billion yen (94 million U.S. dollars) dual currency
note under its Euro Medium Term program.
</P>
<P>
The three-year fixed-rate notes carry an annual coupon of five
percent in yen and an issue price of 98.5 percent. The notes are
redeemable at par, in U.S. dollars. The proceeds of the issue will
be swapped into dollar floating-rate funds.
</P>
<P>
The transaction brings IFC's market borrowing to about 1.28
billion U.S. dollars for the fiscal year 1997, which began on July
1, this year.
</P>
<P>
IFC, an affiliate of the World Bank Group, is the largest
multilateral source of financing for private sector projects in
developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
