<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Provides Federal Funds For Church Burnings Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Tuesday signed into law a bill to finance federal investigations
into the wave of arson fires at black churches in the South.
</P>
<P>
The new law provides 12 million dollars to support the Bureau
of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms' investigation into the church
burnings which are widely believed to be racially motivated.
</P>
<P>
The bureau has more than 100 agents investigating church fires
which have been reported in at least 40 predominantly black
churches across the south east over the past 19 months.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's signature kept a promise he made in June when he
visited the ruins of a black church in Greeleyville, South
Carolina. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Increase Listed Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 7 (Xinhua) -- China hopes to increase the
number of its listed companies in the next five years, bringing
the market value of all publicly traded stocks to 15 percent of
the nation's gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
But the increase in exchange-listed firms should be based
on the demand for capital and market capacity, today's "China
Daily" said.
</P>
<P>
An association of listed firms has been established to guide
their operations, according to a report of the State Commission
for Economic Restructuring.
</P>
<P>
The report said the country should also issue more State
treasury bonds and increase their varieties, especially one-year,
three-month and six-month issues. And outstanding bonds should not
exceed 20 percent of the country's yearly fiscal revenues.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the secondary market for State treasury bonds should
be expanded and increased to ensure smooth trading, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
It also proposed developing investment funds and gradually
increasing institutional investment, to help attract larger
amounts of idle funds to markets that tend to produce quick
returns.
</P>
<P>
The report said the country must speed up the creation of laws
and regulations to govern investment funds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
