<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WFP Concerned Over Famine Victims in Burundi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The World Food Program is concerned
that sanctions imposed on Burundi by its neighboring countries are
preventing humanitarian relief from entering the country and
threatening the well-being of hundreds of thousands of people.
</P>
<P>
WFP was also worried that the cut-off of emergency food,
medicine and fuel supplies could exacerbate ethnic tensions in
Burundi.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions were agreed upon by African leaders at the Arusha
Summit on July 31.
</P>
<P>
"Unless key neighboring countries allow emergency supplies to
enter, the situation is likely to worsen," said WFP spokesman
Trevor Rowe. "This will force WFP to find other more costly
alternatives to deliver food."
</P>
<P>
Currently, WFP estimates it has a one-month stockpile of
emergency supplies in Burundi for an estimated 300,000 people. A
key problem is that once transport operations are shut down, it
requires a long time to restart them. Trucks and drivers must be
found again and contracts renegotiated.
</P>
<P>
"If the situation continues as it is, we'll probably have to
begin seriously worrying in a matter of a couple of weeks because
it will be more difficult to replenish existing stocks," said Rowe.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, WFP is concerned that the Kenyan government today
denied the organization the right to fly its King Air passenger
aircraft to Kenya from Burundi. The move is expected to make it
more difficult for WFP personnel and cargo to transit through
Burundi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
