<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Fibre-Optic Cable in Tibet to Be Built </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The construction of the first
fibre-optic cable linking Tibet and other parts of China will soon
be started and is expected to be finished in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The planned Lanzhou-Xining-Lhasa fibre-optic cable, the most
difficult of its kind in the country, will be built on the
Qinghai-Tibet Plateau, the "roof of the world" about 5,000 meters
above sea level, today's "China Daily" quoted sources from the
Ministry of Posts and Telecommunications (MPT) as saying.
</P>
<P>
Now telephone links between Tibet and other parts of China are
routed through satellites and microwave stations. And there are no
fibre-optic cables so far in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
The cable, extending about 30,000 kilometers, will be designed
and built by the China International Telecommunications
Construction Corporation (CITCC) under the MPT.
</P>
<P>
China now has completed 22 major cross-province fibre-optic
cables linking most provincial capitals except Lhasa, capital of
the Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
Four major fibre-optic cables are expected to be finished by
the end of this year, linking Beijing-Taiyuan-Xi'an,
Shanghai-Hefei-Nanjing-Wuhan, Beijing-Jiujiang-Guangzhou, and
Beijing-Huhhot-Yinchuan-Lanzhou, respectively.
</P>
<P>
And contruction on another seven cables will be launched
between September and December this year, expected to be completed
in the second half in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Austria Condemns U.S. Sanctions on Iran, Libya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Austria today blasted a new
U.S. law punishing foreign firms investing in Iran and Libya,
saying the hardest hit would be small nations doing business with
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Austria "rejects the unilateral U.S. measures" on a third
country and has taken "very serious diplomatic measures" against
them, Foreign Minister Wolfgang Schussel said after a ministerial
council meeting.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the European Union (EU) criticized the legislation,
which, signed by U.S. President Bill Clinton on Monday, provides
for a range of sanctions against foreign companies investing 40
million U.S. dollars or more a year in the oil or gas industries
of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Schussel accused the law of eroding the fruit of world trade
negotiations. He estimated the loss of Austrian business alone at
billions of Austrian schillings (hundreds of millions of dollars).
</P>
<P>
The 15-nation EU, which receives a fifth of its oil supplies
from Iran and Libya, is worried about the long-term impact of the
law and said it is considering retaliatory measures.
</P>
<P>
Though somehow hopeful of a switch in the U.S. policy amid
protests by its allies, Schussel said he is concerned that smaller
nations, which are unable to take revenge, would suffer the most
if larger powers choose not to fight back. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0257 </DOCNO>
