<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Agrees to Help Probe 1980 Italian Air Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 7 (Xinhua) -- NATO has agreed to help Italy
investigate a mysterious 1980 air crash off the Sicilian coast in
which 81 people died, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Italian media have long speculated that the plane was
accidentally shot down by a NATO missile and the Italian
government has repeatedly called the military alliance to release
secret radar charts relating to the crash.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Romano Prodi Tuesday welcomed the decision of
NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana to set up a committee to
investigate the crash and to study relevant radar charts, a
government spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Investigating Judge Rosario Priore also hailed the decision,
saying that he was looking forward to unraveling the cause of the
tragedy.
</P>
<P>
The accident happened on June 27, 1980, near the tiny island of
Ustica, some 60 kilometers north of Sicily, when an Itavia
domestic airline DC-9 crashed, killing 81 people aboard.
</P>
<P>
The committee, consisting of three NATO experts -- one legal,
one security and one military, is expected to meet Italian
investigators later this month, diplomatic sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nicaragua To Take Dispute With Colombia to Hague Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Nicaraguan Foreign Minister
Ernesto Leal said Monday that his country is considering going to
the International Court of Justice in the Hague to resolve a
territorial dispute with Colombia.
</P>
<P>
Direct talks between the two countries on the sovereignty of
the Caribbean islands of San Andres and Providencia are breaking
down, he said.
</P>
<P>
"If this mechanism loses effectiveness, we are going to be
forced to go to the Hague," he said.
</P>
<P>
He had sought dialogue over the two islands off the east coast
of Nicaragua with former Colombian Foreign Minister Rodrigo Pardo
Garcia-Pena, who resigned in early July, Leal added. But, to date,
the most he got was a meeting that bore no fruit, he declared.
</P>
<P>
Leal did not reveal the date on which his government will
submit the dispute to the court.
</P>
<P>
The territorial dispute has been intensified after Colombia
included the two islands as Colombian territory on a map.
</P>
<P>
Nicaragua insists that both islands belong to it and considers
null and void the 1928 Barcenas Meneses-Esquerra Accord, which
ceded the islands, together with other large islands, to
Colombia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Athens Welcomes Olympic Delegation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Fresh from its best performance
in 100 years, the Greek Olympic team returned here Tuesday evening
to be greeted by tens of thousands of Athenians.
</P>
<P>
In a speech at the welcoming party featuring fireworks at
Panathenian Stadium, Prime Minister Costas Simitis highly praised
the achievements that the Greek athletes made at the Olympic Games
at Atlanta, the United States.
</P>
<P>
He said, "Your victory for all of us is a great lesson, showing
that nothing is conquered without toil; that nothing is won
without sacrifices; that nothing is consolidated without effort;
that nothing is ensured without outdoing ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
Greece made its best ever modern Olympic showing at Atlanta,
winning four gold and four silver medals. Five other clinched
fourth place.
</P>
<P>
Greek weightlifters Pyros Dimas and Akakios Kakhiashvili won
gold medals, along with Yiannis Melissanidis in gymnastics and
Nikos Kaklamanakis in the men's yachting event.
</P>
<P>
The weightlifting team also won three silver medals and Niki
Bakoyianni took the other silver in the women's high jump.
</P>
<P>
Before arriving at the stadium, the motorcade stopped by the
Temple of Zeus, where the eight medalists were awarded the ''Gold
Medal of Honour'' by Athens Mayor Dimitris Avramopoulos.
</P>
<P>
All the Olympians who finished among the top eight in their
respective events then proceeded on foot to the packed 80,000-seat
marble stadium, where they were greeted by Greek President Kostis
Stephanopulos, Prime Minister Simitis, ministers and almost all of
the nation's political leadership.
</P>
<P>
The Flag-waving fans lined the road from the airport to the
stadium to welcome the athletes, who displayed their medals from
atop the military jeeps they rode. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
