<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Teachers Declare 24-hour Strike in Colombia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Some 250,000 teachers
in Colombia went on a one-day nationwide strike for higher pay
today, leaving eight million students without classes.
</P>
<P>
The president of the National Federation of Teachers Boris
Monte de Oca said the strike is intended to force the government
to negotiate and change its proposal for a 13 percent
salary increase for state workers in 1997.
</P>
<P>
He said the government had given a commitment to Colombians
through its social leap policy to improve living standards for
low-income families. But the reality had demonstrated the
opposite.
</P>
<P>
A 13 percent salary is of no use when inflation this month is
already 15.5 percent, he added.
</P>
<P>
The teachers' strike is also a protest against the government's
economic policies and U.S. meddling in Colombia's internal
affairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine, Russia to Hold Border Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The first round of border talks
between Ukraine and Russia will be held on August 13-14 in Moscow
to speed up demarcation of their shared boundary and resolve
border cooperation issues, Ukrainian Foreign Minister Gennady
Udovenko said here today.
</P>
<P>
Udovenko stressed Ukraine wants to solve the border issue
legally and in a consultative manner.
</P>
<P>
The current ill-defined boundary line between the two
countries has led to illegal immigration, the Ukrainian National
Information Agency said.
</P>
<P>
During the first seven months of this year, there were as many
as 11 million crossings and 1.6 million tons of goods passed
through the Ukrainian-Russian border. 
</P>
</TEXT>
