<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Commemorates Cinema Centennial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Mexico is commemorating the
100th anniversary of cinematography, brought to the country by the
Lumiere brothers, French film pioneers who revolutionized the
techniques of film making.
</P>
<P>
As part of the celebration, the first exhibition of the Lumiere
brothers' film photography will begin tonight in the National
Museum of History in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
The films the Lumiere brothers offered to General Porfirio
Diaz, the former Mexican president whose dictatorship extended
from 1877 to 1911, will be projected at the celebration.
</P>
<P>
Other celebratory activities include an exhibition of the first
films made by Mexicans, a show of 100 photographs, posters,
photomontage and 20 movie cameras, and a display of costumes and
publications of the era.
</P>
<P>
Film making was introduced to Mexico by Gabriel Veyre and
Calude F. bon Bernard, who represented the French Lumiere company,
between August 4-6, 1896, at the height of Diaz's rule. 
</P>
</TEXT>
