<HEADLINE> Chile to Negotiate Concession of Ports With Bolivia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Chile is willing to negotiate
with Bolivia on the concession of its ports for trade purposes but
not on a sovereign corridor, Foreign Minister Jose Miguel Insulza
said today.
</P>
<P>
Bolivia "is not talking, precisely, about a corridor but rather
about a concession for trade purposes and we are always willing to
examine things like that," the diplomat told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The Chilean government has stated its "full willingness to
discuss the topics related to Bolivian access to Chilean ports on
the Pacific," the Chilean minister said.
</P>
<P>
He said his country is ready to deal with Bolivia about trade
integration and to examine the formulas that would resolve
problems concerning better development of investments, but not to
tackle the issues of a Bolivian outlet to the ocean.
</P>
<P>
He said that "this is a matter that has to do with integration
and it does not mean re-opening or re-examining past issues."
</P>
<P>
Insulza added that Chile is willing to review neither border
nor sovereignty issues with Bolivia because it has no border
problems pending with the neighboring country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
