<HEADLINE> Kuchma, Yeltsin May Meet Over Fleet Issue: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Ukrain has suggested that Russian
President Boris Yeltsin and Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma meet
on Friday to try to solve the continuing row over the separation
of the Black Sea Fleet.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine's Foreign Minister Gennady Udovenko said this at a
press conference today.
</P>
<P>
The dispute between the Ukrainian and Russian navies over the
ownership and use of Sevastopol in Ukraine's Crimea peninsula as a
naval base for the fleet has become an obstacle in the development
of bilateral relations and is blocking the signing of a friendship
treaty between the two countries, Udovenko said.
</P>
<P>
The minister, who held talks in Moscow on the issue last week,
said Ukraine believes the bilateral agreement will be conducive to
solving existing problems, but Russia wants to solve the issue of
the Black Sea Fleet first before signing the agreement.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, in the latest twist in the long-running dispute over
the Black Sea Fleet, the commander of Ukraine's naval forces
accused his Russian counterpart of not taking the issue seriously.
</P>
<P>
Navy chief Vladimir Beskorovainy threatened to annul his
signature on some of the documents concerning the second phase
separation of the fleet after inspecting the 54 warships due to be
transferred to Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
He said the vessels were too old and useless and said Ukraine
should renegotiate the deal.
</P>
<P>
Since the collapse of the Soviet Union in 1991, Ukraine and
Russia have been trying to agree on how to divide the 300-vessel
Soviet Black Sea Fleet based in Sevastopol and on ownership of the
port.
</P>
<P>
The Ukrainian and Russian defense ministries agreed to split
the Black Sea Fleet in two phases. The first phase was completed
in late March.
</P>
<P>
The second phase, dealing with the separation of the remaining
warships and support vessels still moored at Sevastopol, was due
to be completed at the end of May this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
