<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drenched Beijing May Face More Rain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 7 (Xinhua) -- The summer's unusually heavy
rainfall may not be over and could lead to more flooding in the
days ahead, Beijing authorities warned.
</P>
<P>
Flood control agencies were urged to be prepared to help
prevent casualties, "China Daily" reports today.
</P>
<P>
Duan Qiang, vice-mayor of Beijing, called upon municipal
flood-control authorities to be ready to deal with floods caused
by more downpours.
</P>
<P>
So far this week, water levels in 10 out of the city's 16 large
and medium-sized reservoirs have risen above their flood-water
lines. Six of them started discharging excess water on Monday
after the latest downpour, which drenched Beijing Sunday and
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The deluge was caused by a low pressure area pushed across
China's southeast coast last week by Typhoon Herb. An average of
77 millimeters f precipitation was measured in urban areas, the
highest this summer. A high of 154 millimeters of rainfall was
recorded in the city's southwestern sections.
</P>
<P>
A flood peak with a rate of flow reaching 1,720 cubic meters
per second, the highest since 1963 was measured in the Jumahe
River, running through the southern sections of Beijing.
</P>
<P>
By yesterday, more than 12,000 people living in nine villages
in Fangshan County, southwest of Beijing along the river, were
still stranded by the floods from the river's southern and
northern tributaries. No casualties have been reported.
</P>
<P>
Communications in the flood-stricken villages remained
undisturbed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
