<HEADLINE> Colombia Replaces Top Sports Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Colombian President
Ernesto Samper Monday dismissed his top sports official for the
country's poor performance at the just-concluded Olympic Games in
Atlanta, the United States.
</P>
<P>
Samper named Ignacio Pombo Villar to replace Diego Barragan
Correa as head of the Colombian Institute of Youth and Sports,
according to presidential spokesperson Carlos Castillo.
</P>
<P>
The Colombians returned home from Atlanta empty-handed whereas
Ximena Restrepo got the country a bronze medal from the 1992
Olympic Games held in Barcelona, Spain.
</P>
<P>
Castillo said the reshuffle was aimed at revitalizing sports in
the country and striving for a better performance in the 2000
games to be held in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
The new sports head said he will have to find a better way to
spend the government grant of 50 million U.S. dollars to pump new
energy into sports.
</P>
<P>
Outgoing Barragan, who had held the post for only five months,
said Colombian sports had not been given the importance they
deserved.
</P>
<P>
"Should this continue, we are going to face the same debacle
every four years," he said.
</P>
<P>
The presidential spokesperson said Colombia is going to hire
foreign coaches and promote sports among universities in an effort
to improve the country's sporting caliber. 
</P>
</TEXT>
