<HEADLINE> Russia Reiterates Opposition to U.S. Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Russia today reiterated its
opposition to U.S. sanctions against foreign companies that
invest in Iran and Libya.
</P>
<P>
The sanctions will not help stability in the Middle East region
or the international fight against terrorism, Russian Foreign
Ministry spokesman Vladimir Andreyev told a press conference today.
</P>
<P>
He said combatting terrorism requires cooperation rather
than unilateral sanctions, which go against the anti-terrorism
document formulated at the summit of Group Seven and Russia in
Lyon, France, last month.
</P>
<P>
Russia is studying whether the U.S. sanctions will affect
Russian companies.
</P>
<P>
The new U.S. law, signed by President Bill Clinton on Monday,
imposes sanctions on foreign companies that make new investments
of more than 40 million U.S. dollars a year in oil or gas projects
in Iran or Libya, which the United States claims are the chief
state sponsors of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
European countries, threatened to hit back if the law was fully
enforced, saying the United States had no right to dictate where
their companies could invest. Many European oil and gas companies
have significant investments in Iran and Libya. 
</P>
</TEXT>
