<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Astrogeological Catastrophes As Cause of Natural Evolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 7 (Xinhua) -- A number of Chinese scientists
have stated at the 30th International Geological Congress that
catastrophes caused by collisions of the earth and materials from
outer space are a source of the earth's evolution.
</P>
<P>
Such catastrophes resulted in the extinction of ancient forms
of life, such as dinosaurs and trilobites, in sudden changes in
the environment, and in the formation of mineral resources.
</P>
<P>
Xu Daoyi, professor of the Institute of Geology of the State
Seismological Bureau, says that the extinction of ancient forms of
life always occurred with global catastrophes.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the spread of materials from outer-space and
ancient meteorite craters, the presence of iridium shows an
extraordinary increase in the mineral layers corresponding to a
boundary between two geologic eras. This means that sharp changes
in the environment are the result of collisions of the earth and
materials from the depths of space, or a dynamic supernova
explosion near the planet.
</P>
<P>
Xu's idea is supported by other two Chinese scientists
including Zhang Qingwen of the Chinese Academy of Geological
Science and Sun Yiyin of the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
They say that his hypothesis tallies with the results of recent
discoveries in the Cretaceous-Tertiary Era boundaries, which
corresponds to the dying out of dinosaurs and the flourishing of
mammals.
</P>
<P>
Xu and his fellow researchers say that an aerolite 10 km in
diameter fell to earth at that time, causing an increase in carbon
dioxide concentration in the atmosphere, and the death of a great
number of animals because of food shortages.
</P>
<P>
In addition, a supernova explosion dating back 10,500 years,
resulted in an increase in nitrogen density, changing the
proportion of different carbon isotopes. Human-beings are
believed to have made their first steps toward civilization at
that time.
</P>
<P>
In contrast to the astrogeological catastrophe hypothesis, the
supposition that the natural evolution is driven by the inner
forces of the earth has seen little progress in past decades,
according to Xu.
</P>
<P>
"No credible geological evidence has been found supporting the
idea that evolution was caused by tsunami or worldwide chaos in
ocean currents," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
