<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0286 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-06 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Refuses to Discuss Security Arrangements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese House Speaker Nabih
Berri announced here tonight that his country refuses to discuss
security arrangements in south Lebanon, which will facilitate an
Israeli withdrawal from the area.
</P>
<P>
Berri returned home tonight from a short visit to Damascus
where, the Shiite house speaker held talks with Syrian President
Hafez al-Assad, Vice President Abdel-Halim Khaddam and Foreign
Minister Farouq al-Shara.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival at the Beirut Presidential Palace, the house
speaker immediately had a meeting with President Elias Hrawi and
Prime Minister Rafik Hariri and informed them of his talks in the
Syrian capital.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters at the end of the meeting, Berri stressed
that the security arrangements in south Lebanon would "run counter
to Resolution 425 and cancel the resolution."
</P>
<P>
U.N. Security Council Resolution 425, which was adopted in
1978 following an Israeli invasion into this country, calls for an
unconditional withdrawal of the Jewish state from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Israel's "Lebanon First" proposal, the house
speaker said that it was a problem concerning Lebanon and Israel
should not negotiate with Syria over it.
</P>
<P>
He said that his talks in Damascus dealt with a five-nation
committee monitoring cease-fire in south Lebanon, which was
established under an April 26 understanding reached between
Lebanon and the Jewish state. The committee will hold its first
meeting in the southern Lebanese town of Naqura Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The United States, France, Syria, Lebanon and Israel have
appointed their diplomatic and military representatives to the
committee.
</P>
<P>
Berri said that he discussed with the Syrian leaders the
latest developments in the region as well as prominent domestic
problems in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu put forward the
"Lebanon First" proposal in an apparent bid to break the current
dilemma of the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposal, Israel will unilaterally pull its troops
out of a 850-square-kilometer buffer zone in south Lebanon in
exchange for a Syria's help in disarming the pro-Iranian Hezbollah
guerillas and a mechanism safeguarding the security on the
Lebanese-Israeli border.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was on the top of the agenda in a meeting between
Hrawi and al-Assad in Damascus Monday, the second summit of the
two leaders in 20 days.
</P>
<P>
Hrawi summoned to his office this moring the Lebanese prime
minister and house speaker and informed them of his talks with the
Syrian president.
</P>
<P>
Well-informed official sources said that Prime Minister Hariri
would also visit the Syrian capital Wednesday to meet the
Syrian vice president.
</P>
<P>
The intensive Syrian-Lebanon consultations come on the eve of
an expected visit by Syrian President al-Assad Wednesday to
Alexandria, Egypt, where he will have a meeting with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
