<HEADLINE> No Special Grants for Soldiers to Buy Motorbikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's defense headquarters
said today that the money to be provided by the military for
eligible soldiers to procure motorcycles could be loans instead
of generally considered special grants.
</P>
<P>
The military announced days ago to offer money for servicemen
to buy motorcycles as part of the effort to show the desire of
the federal government to make all personnel benefit. But the
move has been believed to be one to provide special grants to
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Defense spokesman Fred Chijuka said in a clarification here
today that modalities would be worked out for repayment, in
accordance with civil service rules.
</P>
<P>
The repayment would be deducted at source from the monthly
salaries of each beneficiary, he said, adding that the military
would also ensure the loan is used for the purpose it was
granted.
</P>
<P>
He said some criteria would be applied to ensure that soldiers
most qualified by hardwork, length of service, necessity and good
character, among others, would benefit.
</P>
<P>
The soldiers have been looking forward "with strong desires
to having the loan since the recommendation for it was offered to
the government for approval, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
