<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Pupils in Zambia Infected With Bilharzia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Three hundred pupils at the Kawama
Primary
School in Chililabombwe, Copperbelt Province of Zambia, have been
infected with the disease of bilharzia.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed by Mohammed Shehata of the National Council
for Scientific Research (Kitwe regional office) today in the
Zambian border town of Chililabombwe.
</P>
<P>
The infection of the bilharzia was first found there in
mid-July. Shehata is heading a team of medical officers sent by
the government to the epidemic area to fight the disease.
</P>
<P>
A news dispatch from Chililabombwe quoted Shehata as saying
that so far 300 pupils are infected with bilharzia out of 415 who
presented urine samples for tests in the last three weeks.
</P>
<P>
"This represents 65 percent of the infection rate at the
school. The situation is acute," said Shehata.
</P>
<P>
Despite the closure of schools in the area because of the
disease, all the 300 pupils found to be suffering from the
disease turned up for free treatment at Kawama Primary School
this morning.
</P>
<P>
Rivers, pools and a dam where the residents in the
Chililabombwe area draw water are heavily infested with snails
that carry parasites with bilharzia germs. "These germs easily
pierce through human skin when the victim steps into the infected
water," Shehata said.
</P>
<P>
Bilharzia affects the brain, liver and spleen, causing anaemia
and cancer to intestines and urinary system in human body.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
