<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-06 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak to Meet Syrian President in Alexandria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
will meet with his Syrian counterpart Hafez al-Assad Wednesday for
talks on the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, to be held in the Egyptian Mediterranean port city
of Alexandria, will mainly deal with the Syrian and Lebanese
tracks of the peace process and Israel's decision to restart
construction of Jewish settlements in the Palestinian territories
of the West Bank and Gaza Strip, Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa told reporters today.
</P>
<P>
The Arabs, particularly the Palestinians, have criticized
Israel's decision on settlements as an obstacle to peace and a
violation of agreements already reached between Israel and the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The Mubarak-al-Assad meeting comes just four days after
al-Assad met with Jordan's King Hussein in Damascus Saturday to
explore ways to revive the stalled Syrian-Israeli peace talks.
</P>
<P>
On Monday in Damascus, al-Assad also held talks with Lebanese
President Elias Hrawi to coordinate their stances on the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has expressed
willingness to resume peace talks with Syria. Syrian newspapers,
which usually reflect the government's views, said today that
Netanyahu's offer to resume talks was not serious because it is
not based on the land-for-peace principle.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has reportedly put forward the so-called "Lebanese
first" proposal, according to which Israel will pull out its
troops from an enclave in south Lebanon in exchange for Syria's
help in disarming Lebanese pro-Iranian Hezbollah guerillas and
security on Israel's northern border with Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
But both Lebanon and Syria rejected the proposal. During their
talks Monday, al-Assad and Hrawi agreed to adopt a common stand on
peace moves with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Syria described the proposal as a "trap" aimed at sabotaging
the good ties between Beirut and Damascus.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said that Wednesday's meeting between Mubarak and al-Assad
comes within the framework of constant Egyptian-Syrian coordination
on the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, the first Arab state to make peace with Israel in 1979,
has been playing an active role in the Mideast peace process as it
acts as a key mediator between the Arabs and Israel in their peace
negotiations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
