<HEADLINE> Bildt, Plavsic Meet in Banja Luka on Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The High Representative of the
international community for Bosnia Carl Bildt said today
constitutional changes were forthcoming in both Bosnian entities
-- Republika Srpska and the Muslim-Croat federation.
</P>
<P>
After meeting acting Serb President Biljana Plavsic behind
closed doors in the northwestern Serb city of Banja Luka, Bildt
said the elections scheduled for September 14 should be followed
by economic reforms in line with the Dayton agreement.
</P>
<P>
The talks had also focused on accelerating the "release of all
prisoners of war (POWs) and the exhumations of remains of the
killed, as both of these processes should be completed before the
elections," the Tanjug news agency quoted Bildt as saying.
</P>
<P>
In a brief statement to the press, Plavsic said that every
meeting with Bildt gave an impetus to the implementation of the
Dayton agreement to which the Serbs remain firmly committed, and
that the provision on POWs release was particularly important as
this process had been due to be completed by January 19 under the
Dayton agreement.
</P>
<P>
Plavsic, who assumed all presidential duties from former
President Radovan Karadzic last month, also pointed to problems
hindering the exhumations of bodies of Serb soldiers and civilians
from mass graves in Glamoc and Sanski Most in the west and on Mt.
Ozren in the north, due to the interference of Muslim-Croat
federation authorities.
</P>
<P>
She also said that Bildt and his staff were working to put an
end to the suffering of the people whose kins are either dead or
in jail, although facing the truth would be very painful for many.
</P>
</TEXT>
