<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France to Inaugurate 36th Bridge Over Seine River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- France will inaugurate its 36th
bridge over the Seine River flowing through Paris -- the Charles
de Gaulle Bridge -- Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
According to the Paris Mayor's Office, the bridge, 208 meters
long and 30 meters wide, will link up two areas of the city in the
momentum of development on both sides of the river -- Bercy on the
right bank and Paris-Rive-Gauche on the left bank, which has the
Great Library of France nearby.
</P>
<P>
The bridge will also link two major railway stations of Paris
on the two sides of the river -- the Gares of Lyon and the Gares
of Austerlitz, and will relieve the neighboring Bridge Austerlitz,
which is the most used bridge in Paris by both traffic and
pedestrians.
</P>
<P>
The bridge was designed by architects Louis Arretche and Roman
Karasinski, both of whom are now dead. It is entirely white, light
in weight, has no curve, looks like a plane wing brushing the
Seine, and is located in a position from which one can sight the
tower of the Notre Dame cathedral.
</P>
<P>
The bridge was named in 1990 by the then mayor of Paris Jacques
Chirac to mark the 100th anniversary of the birth of General de
Gaulle.
</P>
<P>
The construction of the bridge costs 240 million francs (48
million U.S. dollars) and 3,000 tons of steel and 2,000 tons of
concrete were used to build it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960807.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bosnian Muslims Attack UN Bus Transporting Serbs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, August 6 (Xinhua) -- One Bosnian Serb woman was
seriously injured and several others were lightly hurt when a
UNHCR bus was attacked by a group of Muslims on a road passing
through the eastern part of the Muslim-Croat federation in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
The incident took place between Osanica and Kravinjac in the
municipality of Gorazde in eastern Bosnia. Gorazde is a
Muslim-dominated city connected with the Bosnian capital of
Sarajevo through a corridor carved in the Serb territory.
</P>
<P>
This was the second attack on a bus operating on the
Srbinje-Visegrad line introduced by the U.N. High Commissioner for
Refugees (UNHCR) on July 12, the Tanjug news agency reported from
Srbinje, a town in the eastern part of the Serb entity Republika
Srpska.
</P>
<P>
According to Tanjug, all the windows on the bus were broken
after the Muslims threw stones at the bus and the engine was so
damaged that the vehicle could not continue its journey.
</P>
<P>
The most seriously injured was Mira Vilotic, 41, a refugee from
Gorazde. She was taken by a peace Implementation Force (IFOR)
vehicle to Srbinje hospital where doctors took out two glass
particles from her eye.
</P>
<P>
Other passengers who were lightly injured were also taken to
Srbinje hospital for treatment.
</P>
<P>
Under the Dayton agreement, freedom of movement in Bosnia is
guaranteed and the road from Srbinje to Visegrad via Gorazde has
the status of a Blue Route patroled by IFOR troops.
</P>
<P>
Tanjug said traffic is functioning normally without any
incidents on all roads in Republika Srpska, which are also used
by buses from the Muslim-Croat federation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
