<HEADLINE> French Franc Dives Lowest in 4 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The French franc today dived to its
lowest point in four months in exchange rates with 3.4060 francs
for one mark, as compared with 3.3998 francs for one mark Monday.
</P>
<P>
Agence France Presse (AFP) said that the drop of the franc's
value is due to fears of new strikes to be held by public sector
employees in September and the uncertainty over the capability of
the government to cut spending.
</P>
<P>
Investors, most of them foreigners, are selling francs at the
moment against a background of social turbulence in September, AFP
quoted analyst Jean-Jacques Salabi of Fx Concept as saying.
</P>
<P>
The government is expected to lay off 8,000-9,000 public sector
employees, most of them teachers in public schools, next month.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it is not clear whether the government of Prime
Minister Alain Juppe will be able to cut no less than 2 percent of
ministerial budgets due to be announced by Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Inflation in France now stands at 2 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
