<HEADLINE> UN Calls on Somalia to Reach Peaceful Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Security Council today called upon all factions in Somalia to use
the current situation for a lasting truce and peaceful settlement
to their conflicts.
</P>
<P>
German Ambassador Antonius Eitel, council president for August,
said in a statement to the press that the Security Council briefly
discussed the developments in Somalia and council members expressed
their concern about the situation there today.
</P>
<P>
The council urged all factions in Somalia to refrain from any
action that might lead to a further worsening.
</P>
<P>
After Somali warlord Mohamed Farah Aideed died of gunshot
wounds last Thursday, his enemies expressed the intention to join
peace talks to form a new government. When the warlord's son
Hussein took over as faction leader in the country, enemies of
Aideed in Somalia said Monday his followers had thrown away a
chance for peace and their forces were on alert. 
</P>
</TEXT>
