<HEADLINE> Serbian, Croatian Presidents to Meet in Athens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Serbian President Slobodan
Milosevic and his Croatian counterpart, Franjo Tudjman, will meet
in Athens Wednesday to discuss normalization of ties, the
Yugoslavia news agency Tanjug said today.
</P>
<P>
This would be the first top-level meeting between Serbian and
Croatian leaders on bilateral relations since Croatia declared
independence from the former Yugoslavia in the summer of 1991.
</P>
<P>
Tanjug said the talks would focus on "issues of importance for
promoting Yugoslav-Croatian relations."
</P>
<P>
Yugoslavia, which is comprised of Serbia and Montenegro,
recognized the former Yugoslav republics of Bosnia-Herzegovina
last December and Macedonia in April this year. The negotiation on
normalization of relations with Slovenia and Croatia has been
under way but in a slow process.
</P>
<P>
Mutual recognition between Yugoslavia and Croatia, the two
powerful countries in the region, is seen as crucial for a
permanent peace in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
The major obstacles on the way include the dispute over the
Prevlaka peninsula bordering Croatia and Yugoslavia in the south
and the Eastern Slavonia region on the border in the north.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
