<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Troops in Saudi Moving to New Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The United States has
dispatched the first of about 1,200 military personnel to a remote
air base in Al Khari, Saudi Arabia, for the preparation of a large
bulk of 4,000 American troops moving to the facility, the Pentagon
announced today.
</P>
<P>
The movement is part of the plan drawn up by the Pentagon to
enhance security measures following the June 25 truck bombing at
an air base near Dhahran that killed 19 U.S. soldiers and
injured several hundred.
</P>
<P>
Pentagon spokesman Ken Bacon said these military personnel,
largely engineers and logistics specialists, will undertake the
tasks of constructing hundreds of air-conditioned tents to shelter
those being moved to Al Khari's Prince Sultan Air Base, about 55
miles southeast of Riyadh.
</P>
<P>
He said the move has been designed to avoid interrupting the
mission of American, French and British forces stationed in the
kingdom to monitor the no-fly zone over southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Defense Secretary William Perry has expected the move to
be completed within two to six weeks.
</P>
<P>
About 750 dependents of U.S. military personnel residing in
Saudi Arabia are expected to return to the United States within
one to two weeks for safety purpose, according to Perry's order.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
